<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, March 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Congress star campaign and widow of former prime
minister Rajiv Gandhi Sonia Gandhi was appointed new Congress
president here Saturday to replace Sitaram Kesri.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this, senior party leader Sharad Pawar said Sonia
Gandhi would preside over a meeting of the Congress Working
Committee (CWC), the highest policy-making body of the party,
convened here at 17:30 (local time) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In search of a charismatic and able leader, CWC in its meeting
on Saturday morning appointed Sonia Gandhi as new party president,
removing incumbent Sitaram Kesri, whose resignation was not
confirmed yet.
</P>
<P>
"To remove the confusion and state of uncertainty leading to
irreparable and immense harm to the party (in the wake of Kesri's
announcement on Monday to resign), the CWC resolves to appoint
Sonia Gandhi as the president of Indian National Congress in
exercise of its powers conferred in clause (j) of article 19 of
the party constitution with immediate effect," said a resolution
adopted at the CWC meeting on Saturday. (India-Congress-President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The First Session of the Ninth National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
ended here Saturday after completing its agenda.
</P>
<P>
The session has elected a new trans-century leadership of
China's top advisory body. (China-CPPCC-First Session-Closure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian President Soeharto announced here
Saturday the formation of his new cabinet for the 1998-2003 period.
</P>
<P>
This is Indonesia's seventh cabinet under the leadership of
President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was re-elected on March 10 to his seventh term of
office by the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) at its general
session. (Indonesia-Soeharto-Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Head of the U.N. special group of international
experts and senior diplomats designated to inspect Iraqi
presidential palaces, Sri Lankan Jayanatha Dhanapala, left here
Saturday after a four-day visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Dhanapala held talks with Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid,
and discussed measures to visit Iraqi presidential sites
according to the Iraq-U.N. memorandum of understanding signed last
month.
</P>
<P>
They have reportedly agreed to carry out inspections to
presidential sites later this month. (Iraq-UN) 
</P>
</TEXT>
