<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Pressing World Cup Organizing Committee Over Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union Competition
Commissioner Karel Van Miert is still pressing the French
Organizing Committee (CFO), the body responsible for distributing
World Cup football match tickets, to free up more seats for
non-French fans.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting Thursday between CFO representatives and
officials of the European Commission, the EU's executive body, the
commissioner told the European Parliament in Strasbourg that the
organizers were still dragging their feet over his calls to allocate
the remaining 110,000 unsold tickets to supporters from other EU
member states.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the EU executive might decide to send a formal
"statement of objections" to the seat allocation system if the CFO
did not bow to pressure by early in the week beginning March 16.
</P>
<P>
Commission competition officials have been in talks with the CFO
for several weeks over complaints that the ordering method
established for individual fans to obtain match tickets to the
French World Cup discriminates against non-French citizens.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive believes that the CFO is abusing its dominant
market position with its distribution system.
</P>
<P>
Theoretically the commission may impose fines for such breaches
of community law, but officials have hitherto been playing down the
punitive options and seeking a practical solution to the problem,
according to an informed EU source.
</P>
<P>
Van Miert suggested to the parliament's plenum Thursday that the
"wise thing to do" would now be to reserve the still-unallocated
110,000 tickets exclusively for non-French customers since France
had already absorbed 37 percent of the total seats available.
</P>
<P>
"We want to compensate -- as far as it is still possible -- for
the discrimination already suffered by the other European
countries," the commissioner told the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the CFO still wants to be able to sell them to
all-comers, including French enquirers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
