<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Hussein Visits U.S. on Arafat's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official said
Saturday that it was upon Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's
request that King Hussein of Jordan was paying an official visit
to the United States starting from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat asked for the king's interference in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks that had been stalled since March
1997 due to the Israeli government's hardline policy, Jordan's
Deputy Prime Minister for Services and Minister of Information
Abdullah Nsour told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Upon the Palestinian leader's demand, Hussein would use his
"good offices" with U.S. President Bill Clinton in a bid to
breathe new life into the Middle East peace process which was now
facing many difficulties, he added.
</P>
<P>
The king and Clinton are scheduled to hold talks in Washington
on March 19, Nsour said.
</P>
<P>
Hussein will reiterate Jordan's stand that the peace process
should be put back on track through honoring the signed agreements
between the Israelis and Palestinians, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Hussein's visit came after he concluded a six-day Arab tour
which included talks with the leaders of Egypt, the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and Oman.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Hassan paid visits to Ramallah, West Bank and Tel
Aviv on Monday and Tuesday for talks with Palestinian and Israeli
officials.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hussein will also exert efforts to procure more
U.S. aid for Jordan. The U.S. aid for the kingdom in the fiscal
year of 1998 is estimated at around 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been an active mediator in the Middle East peace
process. It had helped hammer out the Hebron accord between the
Palestinians and Israelis at the beginning of last year, under
which Israel promised to evacuate most of the occupied land in the
West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
