<HEADLINE> Pakistan Declares Indian Official Persona-non-grata </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
Saturday declared P.N. Nair, an official of the Indian High
Commission, persona-non-grata in the wake of a spate of terrorist
bombings in the country, which have claimed the lives of many
innocent persons.
</P>
<P>
"P.N. Nair was found indulging in activities incompatible with
his official status," said a press release issued by the Foreign
Office Saturday night, adding that he has been asked to leave
Pakistan within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Deputy High Commissioner was summoned to the Foreign
Office on Saturday and told that the government of Pakistan had
incontrovertible evidence of the involvement of P.N. Nair in acts
of espionage and subversion, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Deputy High Commissioner was further told that
Indian intelligence agencies were actively sponsoring acts of
sabotage and terrorism in Pakistan, which had not only led to
tragic loss of life but were also a blatant violation of the U.N.
Charter and international norms proscribing terrorism, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
A few days earlier, the release said that a strong protest had
been lodged by Pakistan with the government of India at the
organized and symptomatic campaign of terrorism launched by Indian
intelligence agencies against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has also briefed heads of the missions representing
the five Permanent Members of the U.N. Security Council on Indian
sponsored terrorist acts in Pakistan and called for universal
condemnation, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
