<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denies Secret Talks With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Minister of Transportation
Omar Miskawi Saturday denied Israeli reports on secret talks
between Lebanese and Israeli officials, Egypt's Voice of the Arabs
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon is in no need to have secret talks with Israel,"
Miskawi told the Cairo-based radio, adding that Lebanon and
Syria will hold consulations in Damascus later Saturday on the
latest developments in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
As for the Israeli proposal on implementing U.N. Resolution 425
in return for security safeguards, Miskawi said that Lebanon has
not received anything in this regard whether directly or
indirectly.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon still insists on the necessity of implementing
U.N. Resolution 425 unconditionally," he added.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted in 1978 after Israel first invaded
Lebanon calls on Israel to withdraw its forces from Lebanon
without delay.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said recently that
Israeli troops were prepared to withdraw from south Lebanon on
condition that Beirut cooperates on security arrangements in the
area.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a "security zone" in south Lebanon in 1985 to
protect its northern towns from across border attacks by Shiite
Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas fighting to end Israeli occupation.
</P>
</TEXT>
