<HEADLINE> Campaign Launched in Zimbabwe to Fight Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Freedom From Hunger
Campaign (ZFFHC), together with the Ministry of Education, Sport
and Culture, Saturday launched a campaign to fight drug abuse
among school children.
</P>
<P>
The campaign called, Youth Against Drug Abuse, is aimed at
promoting awareness among youths, particularly students, on the
dangers of drug and alcohol abuse, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the campaign, youths will be encouraged to speak out on
drug abuse and find ways of preventing themselves from abusing
drugs and live healthy life-styles.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony here, ZFFHC Executive
Director Joyce Chikara said her organisation would facilitate
various anti-drug programs that include launching awareness and
educational campaigns through quiz competitions, essay writing,
drug forums, poetry and dramas.
</P>
<P>
''Drugs have been drafted into the lives of innocent and
unsuspecting youths under the guise of pleasure, relief of
boredom, prescriptions of courage prestige and the in-thing
syndrome,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
She said researches carried out between 1990 and 1994 in
secondary schools in Harare and other places showed a disturbing
prevalence of the use of tobacco, alcohol, inhalants and cannabis
by students.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Mayor of Harare Alderman Edward Mapuranga urged local
authorities, the government, non-governmental organisations and
the private sector to work together to resolve the problem which
he said, is destroying family ties and derailing production in
industry and commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
