<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Retaliates Against EU Production Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Spain has "totally rejected" the
production quota of olive oil set for it by the European
Commission, the European Union (EU)'s executive body, in the
commission's draft proposals to reform the sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the quota, Spain will only be allowed to produce
600,000 tons of olive oil per annum for the next three years. The
figure only constitutes 60 percent of Spain's capacity, according
to European Report, a newsletter published in Brussels Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive is expected to unveil its proposals for the
next wave of reform of the Common Agricultural Policy on March 18,
including a draft regulation on the Common Market Organization for
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
Whereas before the olive oil quota was given as an EU total,
the commission's proposals due to be published on March 18 will
introduce the concept of Maximum Guaranteed Quotas (MGQ) on a
national basis.
</P>
<P>
Under the MGQ system, savings on small producers' aid and
consumption aid will be translated into tonnage and distributed
appropriately among the member states involved.
</P>
<P>
Thus Ita will probably be awarded 501,172 tons, Greece 339,038
tons, Portugal 43,915 tons and France 3,065 tons, bringing the EU
total to 1,562,400 tons.
</P>
<P>
Barring the largest producer, Spain, the Mediterranean
countries are by and large satisfied with their potential quotas.
</P>
<P>
When the commission's proposal is unveiled on March 18, these
countries would potentially have had a blocking vote of 30, enough
to sink the draft regulation.
</P>
<P>
However, the maneuver of converting the EU maximum quota to
specific national MGQs may have the effect of breaking up the
possible alliance, thereby increasing the likelihood of success of
reforming this stubborn sector.
</P>
<P>
Spain produced 947,000 tons of oil last year, over a third more
than it will be allowed next year. In view of the disparity,
Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio said the "fair"
guaranteed maximum quantity should be 781,200 tons.
</P>
<P>
EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler said that the extra
oil being consumed in Northern countries was being offset by a
falling demand in producer countries, namely Spain, Portugal and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
The commission believes that 600,000 tons is justified,
considering that "there is currently a stock of 180,000 tons of
olive oil in the EU that can't be sold."
</P>
<P>
Spain has retaliated by claiming that it can sell the extra oil
on world markets, where demand is slowly but surely increasing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
