<HEADLINE> EU Drops World Cup Threat to Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) foreign
ministers holding a two-day informal meeting in Edinburgh Saturday
dismissed the idea of kicking Yugoslavia out of this year's
football World Cup finals as a sanction on Yugoslavia over the
Kosova crisis.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Foreign Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen, who is attending
the meeting, Friday suggested expelling Yugoslavia's national
football team if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic failed to
open talks with Kosovans on the autonomy for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But his counterparts from Britain, France and Germany all
raised objections to the move.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told a news conference
that a World Cup ban was not within the competence of the EU while
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said political sports
boycotts had not produced the desired results in the past.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said that the idea had
been dropped by the six-nation Contact Group at its meeting in
London last Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the meeting urged Milosevic to open negotiations or face
further sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
