<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-14 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Heralds Changes in Iran's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Saturday heralded major changes in the country's economic
management system, the evening daily Etelaat reported.
</P>
<P>
"We should reconsider our economic management, both in
domestic and foreign fields," Khatami said in an interview with
the state-run television, which would be broadcast later Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate on the government's plans on how to change
the country's economic management system, but underlined the
importance of competition to spur creativity in the economic
sector.
</P>
<P>
The president said that his government was intent on
invigorating economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
He assured the nation that the government would create
stability and security for investments and production, and through
boosting investment security, it would encourage private
investment in the stimulus projects.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, government spokesman Ataollah Mohajerani
announced that the government has decided to ease its control
over state-own companies and would transfer state-owned companies
to private and cooperative sectors.
</P>
<P>
Khatami termed economic issues as the most urgent ones facing
the country, saying that "we can not achieve desirable progress in
political and cultural fields without a balanced economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government attached special attention to
economic issues, saying that over one third of the government's
high-level meetings focused on economic issues since the
government came to power last August.
</P>
<P>
Despite all kinds of problems the country is facing, Khatami
expressed optimism over the future of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
With a sharp reduction of oil incomes in 1997 due to oil price
drops, the Iranian government was facing some serious economic
problems such as budget deficit, high inflation, unemployment and
price hikes.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian people expected Khatami to make major economic
reforms to improve their economic status following the
government's achievements in its foreign policies, particularly
after the improvement of relations with regional states and
European countries.
</P>
<P>
Economists here hold that Khatami's government would focus its
efforts on encouraging investments of the private sectors in
non-oil fields in order to reduce the country's dependence on oil
incomes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
