<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Lebanese Group Launches Attack on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A newly-established Lebanese
anti-Israeli group Saturday launched its first attack on Israeli
forces to commemorate 20 years of Israeli occupation, the
official National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Lebanese Brigades of Resistance to Israeli
Occupation (LBRIO) said one of its units early Saturday morning
attacked an Israeli post inside its occupied south Lebanon with
heavy guns and missiles.
</P>
<P>
The assault destroyed the post's artillery emplacement and
some infrastructure and wounded some Israeli soldiers, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that other two units also took part in the attacks on
Israeli posts on the edge of the occupied security zone.
</P>
<P>
The LBRIO, founded last November by the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, also announced that from Saturday on,
it formally entered the battle field to resist Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah's Secretary General Hassan Nasrallah had said the
aim to set up the LBRIO is to make it possible for the largest
number of people to participate in the struggle against Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in
south Lebanon in 1985 with the declared aim to protect its
northern towns and villages from cross-border guerrillas attack,
Lebanese anti-occupation resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been continuing in the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
