<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Federal Surplus Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian federal government
had a surplus of 3.3 billion dollars (2.3 billion U.S. dollars)
for the first 10 months of the current fiscal year, said reports
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus represents a 10.7 billion dollar turnaround from a
deficit of 7.3 billion dollars reported for the first 10 months of
1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Rising revenue, falling program spending and lower interest
rates helped engineer the turnaround, according to the Finance
Department.
</P>
<P>
Compared with a year earlier, government revenues were up 6.2
billion dollars to 119.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, spending was off 3.4 billion dollars to 79.5
billion dollars, and debt charges were down 1 billion dollars to
36.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The surplus, which was forecast in February's budget, will
allow the government to increase spending, cut taxes and balance
the budget for this fiscal year, which ends this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
