<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Expects Resumption of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides has said that there are possibilities that
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash would be brought back to the
negotiating table, Cyprus News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that this depends very much on the position
the U.N. Security Council and Europe will adopt.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remarks in an interview with London Greek
Radio before the upcoming visit to the region by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's Special Advisor for Cyprus,
Diego Cordovez.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez has announced in New York that he will travel to
Cyprus next Tuesday for talks with two Cypriot communities'
leaders on resumption of the bicommunal negotiations. He will
also visit Athens and Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said if Denktash does not seriously consider the
appeal of the U.N. Security Council, then the next step would be
both the U.N. secretary-general and the Security Council to
consider whether they can continue the U.N. chief's mission
of good offices.
</P>
<P>
They will also have to consider what measures should be taken
against the Turkish Cypriot side, if it does not respond
positively.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Friday expressed concern over the
"high level of tension" in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Abdoulie Momodou Sallah of Gambia, who chaired a
Security Council meeting Friday, said the members of the council
call upon both parties to take practical steps necessary to
move the negotiating process forward in an effective manner.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the Cyprus problem is entering a phase in which
Denktash cannot any longer declare he will not negotiate unless
the U.N.-led peace talks are held between two "independent
states", as the Turkish Cypriot leader has said.
</P>
<P>
Denktash announced recently that the Turkish Cypriots will
not participate in the U.N.-led peace negotiations and Cyprus'
accession talks with the European Union (EU) unless his breakaway
state unilaterally declared in 1983 in Turkish-occupied northern
Cyprus is recognized.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-led peace talks between the two
communities' leaders were held last summer, but the talks ended
in failure due to Denktash's refusal of further negotiations
following EU decision to start accession talks with the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has ordered suspension of bicommunal contacts since
last December in retaliation to the EU Luxembourg summit's
reaffirmation of its decision to start accession talks with
Cyprus on March 31.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and took over the northern third in the wake of a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved despite the U.N. and
international community's peace efforts for the past 24 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
