<HEADLINE> Malaria Threatens Millions of Tanzanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- About 2.8 million people
in Tanzania are at the risk of contracting the malaria epidemic,
according to a report by the Ministry of Health and the World
Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The report, titled "Guidelines for Epidemic Preparedness for
Malaria in Tanzania," says that 10 percent of the country's
population are suffering from the disease.
</P>
<P>
The report was made available here Friday at the start of a
10-day workshop on epidemic preparedness and control of malaria.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, jointly organized by the Ministry of Health and
the WHO, is being attended by district medical and health
officials from 20 districts in 10 regions.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss guidelines for preparedness for
malaria in Tanzania and exchange experience in handling the
epidemic disease.
</P>
<P>
They will also make trips to selected villages where they will
have practical training such as spraying insecticide.
</P>
<P>
Malaria may break out in the regions of Mbeya, Iringa, Dodoma,
Singida and Kagera, Kigoma, Kilimanjaro, Tanga, Arusha, among
others, the workshop was told.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 10,110 Tanzanians contracted malaria,
2,281 of which died of the communicable disease, statistics
indicated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
