<HEADLINE> Egypt Welcomes Warm-up in Relations With Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Amid increasing signs of improved
relations with Sudan, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
Saturday voiced pleasure over the recent detente between the two
Nile neighbors, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy with the amelioration in Cairo-Khartoum ties
which are proceeding very positively," Moussa told reporters after
receiving a copy of credentials of new Sudanese Ambassador to
Egypt Ahmed Abdel Halim Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will hold talks with his Sudanese counterpart Mustafa
Ismail in Cairo on March 23 on the sidelines of meetings of the
Arab League Council, the Sudanese ambassador told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili met with Sudanese
Minister of Trade Osman el-Hadi, who is now visiting here.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed ways of increasing the volume of trade
exchange between the two countries, said Goweili after the talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Sudanese minister proposed purchasing new
Egyptian railway coaches and equipment as part of a plan to
upgrade the Sudanese railways.
</P>
<P>
After a hiatus of more than three years, Egypt resumed the
river Nile navigation from the Egyptian High Dam to the Sudanese
port of Halfa in mid-February, a move hailed by both sides as a
sign of improving relations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt accused Sudan of sheltering Egyptian militants bent on
installing a strict Islamic state in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Cairo said Khartoum supported an attempt to kill President
Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa in 1995. Sudan denied the charge and
blasted Egypt for letting in members of Sudanese opposition
groups. 
</P>
