<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Reach Agreement on Accession Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) foreign
ministers meeting in the Scottish capital Edinburgh Saturday
reached agreement on opening accession talks with Cyprus after
France moved its hurdle out of the way.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the final press conference after two-day informal
talks, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, whose country is the
current EU president, said, "We now have agreement on how to
proceed with Cyprus at the meeting of the 31st (March)," when the
15-nation bloc will kick off its planned accession talks with
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Slovenia, Estonia and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The British presidency proposal does not make a joint
Greek-Turkish Cypriot delegation a condition for negotiations, nor
does it make the resolution of the division of Cyprus an explicit
condition for accession.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, French President Jacques Chriac said that the
EU should freeze its accession talks with Cyprus if the divided
island failed to form a joint delegation for the membership talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greece had also threatened to block the entire EU
accession process if Cyprus was frozen out of the EU enlargement
process.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to meet the French concerns, Britain amended the
EU opening statement as "our objective remains a united Cyprus"
instead of saying "our objective means the accession of a united
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine gave the French green
light to the EU agreement early Saturday after having an emergency
telephone consultation with top French leaders on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, Vedrine noted that it was "neither desirable nor
realistic" that Cyprus be admitted while it was still divided,
since that would only reinforce the division of the island.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos voiced his country's
satisfaction to the agreement by saying, "It is now a reality in
the text that the beginning of the negotiations, the conduct of
the negotiations, the conclusion of the negotiations and
ratification will proceed in the same way for all countries."
</P>
<P>
At Saturday's session, the EU foreign ministers also discussed
fresh EU efforts in revitalizing the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who is due to start a Middle East tour from Sunday, told
the press conference, "There was unanimous agreement that we
should make clear that we do not support expansions of
settlements."
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary also noted that he had no
intention of canceling his planned visit to the Har Homa site in
Arab East Jerusalem despite strong opposition to this particular
visit in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I should make that clear in the course of my visit by visiting
Har Homa," Cook said, adding the EU minister supported a British
presidency initiative of building confidence in the Middle East
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
