<HEADLINE> Canada's Foreign Debt Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada's net indebtedness to
foreigners is increasing, hitting a record 339 billion dollars
(237 billion U.S. dollars) last year, said a report Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the same time, foreign debt is shrinking as a proportion of
the country's gross domestic product (GDP), according to the
Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada figures showed that Canada's gross liability
to foreigners -- foreign investment in Canada -- reached 889
billion dollars at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
And Canadian investment in foreign countries was 550 billion
dollars. The difference between the two was 339 billion dollars,
up 2.5 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
But thanks to strong growth in the Canadian economy, foreign
debt now occupies a smaller share of the country's GDP.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, foreign debt was 39 percent of its GDP,
compared with a recent peak of 45 percent in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
