<HEADLINE> Gulf States Hold Joint Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Armed forces from the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states began a joint military exercise
Saturday in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) in a bid to further
strengthen cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
The GCC joint exercise, code-named "Pennisula Shield-6," is the
sixth since it was launched in 1983, the UAE's official Wam news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, which are being held under a decision by the GCC
defense ministers at the end of last year, are aimed at "improving
combat capabilities of GCC troops...and acquainting the troops
with the most advanced arms," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
It gave no further details of the war game, but said earlier
that "a number of naval, ground and air forces" and GCC's
collective troops "Pennisula Shield," established in early
1990, were involved.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a political, economic and defense alliance formed in
1981 groups the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain and
Oman.
</P>
<P>
In the past years, the regional bloc's members have sought to
improve their self-defense capabilities through holding military
exercises and purchasing advanced weapons.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the GCC defense ministers approved two military
projects including setting up a common radar network for naval and
air surveillance and an early warning system covering all the GCC
states, as well as raising the strength of the "Pennisula Shield"
from 4,000 to 25,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
However, due to their relatively limited human resources, the
GCC states still remain heavily reliant on foreign military
presence to protect their security.
</P>
<P>
The United States deploys some 20,000 troops and 30 combat and
support ships in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
