<HEADLINE> E. African Countries Share Lot in Cooperation: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 14 (Xinhua) - The East African
Cooperation (EAC) nations have achieved tremendous progress in
confidence building and policies harmonization on a wide range of
sectors, the EAC Executive Secretary said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Francis Muthaura, the EAC Executive Secretary, in his
statement to mark the second anniversary of EAC, said that a high
consensus has been reached among the member states Tanzania,
Kenya and Uganda in regional integration, mutual benefit and
equitable development strategy.
</P>
<P>
"The convertibility of the currencies of the member states
has, for example, harmonized macro-economic framework and
promoted the movement of goods, services and factors of
production with the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura, whose secretariat is based in Tanzania's northern
city of Arusha, said that a tripartite agreement on avoidance of
double taxation has been put into practice and a tripartite road
transport agreement and an inland waterway transport agreement
will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
"These measures have boosted cross border trade and investment
in the region," he said, adding that plans have been made to pool
and share resources in the energy, transport, communications and
others sectors.
</P>
<P>
On the proposed upgrading of the cooperation into a treaty
level, Muthaura said he expected the treaty will give a new
impetus to institutionalization of a deeper and wider political
and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The executive secretary disclosed that a donors' two-day
meeting, co-sponsored by the European Union and the World Bank,
was planned on May 25 in Arusha, hoping donors will fund an
ambitious 4.5 billion U.S. Dollars road network in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, a lot still remains to be done," Muthaura noted, "but
all indications show that we are moving on the right track on the
base of the gains over the past two years."  
</P>
</TEXT>
