<HEADLINE> AL Criticizes U.S. Interference in Iraqi Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid Saturday accused the United States of meddling with
other countries' internal affairs when it brands Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein as a "war criminal."
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid was speaking to reporters a day after the
U.S. Senate voted to urge the creation of a United Nations
Tribunal to try Saddam Hussein as an international war criminal.
</P>
<P>
"Such matters which constitute interference in domestic affairs
are categorically rejected," he said before leaving here for Doha,
Qatar, to take part in the meetings of the foreign ministers of
the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) due to open on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In his pre-departure statement, Abdel-Meguid said he will seize
the opportunity of the OIC meetings to push for a solution
to the Libya-West dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Arab leader will invite the Seven-Man Committee of Arab
countries on the Libya crisis to coordinate stances prior to a
U.N. Security Council meeting on the Libya case in New York on
March 20.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Arab countries have to capitalize on a ruling the
International Court of Justice (ICJ) made in favor of Libya and
work toward lifting sanctions against it.
</P>
<P>
The ICJ 15-member bench decided on February 27 that it has the
jurisdiction to try the two Libyan suspects in the 1988 bombing of
a Pan-Am plane over Lockerbie, Scotland, in which 270 people were
killed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed air, arms and diplomatic
embargoes against Libya in 1992 to back up the U.S. and British
demands to try them in either country, which Libya refused.
</P>
</TEXT>
