<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Reassured by Policy to Prolong Land Contract System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in the birthplace of
China's rural reform voice their support to the policy of
extending farmland contract system for another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The message from farmers in Xiaogang Village, in Fengyang
County of east China's Anhui Province, was brought to the ongoing
First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) by He
Chengguo, mayor of Chuzhou City which has jurisdiction over
Fengyang County.
</P>
<P>
In his Government Work Report, Premier Li Peng reiterated the
central government's policies on stabilizing the rural household
responsibility contract system with renumeration linked to
production and extending farmland contract term for another 30
years.
</P>
<P>
"The farmers feel reassured," NPC deputy He Chengguo said. He
had personally went to solicit opinions from farmers in the
Xiaogang village before he came to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The name of the Village has related most closely to China's
rural reform since an event that occurred there 20 years ago when
farmers lived during the period of the People's Commune.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, needy and farmers in Xiaogang divided farmland
owned by the collective among individual households, with 18
elderly villagers fingerprinting on a certificate of security.
</P>
<P>
Afterward, the villagers were very pleased to get in one good
harvest after another.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping, chief architect of China's reform and opening to
the outside world, summed up the experience of these villagers and
termed it as a "responsibility contract system with renumeration
linked to production", and then spread the system to other parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The certificate with 18 red fingerprints on it is now being
kept in the China History Museum in Beijing, giving evidence to
the first step of the country's reform.
</P>
<P>
The contract system brought about miraculous changes among
Chinese farmers. Despite grave natural disasters every year in
some places, there have been consecutive good harvests, with the
state having abundant grain reserves and and rural households
storing surplus grain.
</P>
<P>
According to NPC deputy Liu Shiming from central China's Henan
Province, where a large proportion of its population are engaged
in agriculture, there used to be absurdities spreading in his home
town that contracted farmland would be taken back and managed by
the collective. And many farmers had relaxed their efforts in
farming.
</P>
<P>
"Farmland is our lifeline and hope. If we farmers have our own
land to till, we're holding a stable rice bowl in our hands," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
Li Bingliang, another NPC deputy from Hebei Province, north
China, said the contract system can be applied to either one
household with relatively low productivity or contractors doing
mechanized farming.
</P>
<P>
"The system remains the most popular among the farmers," Li
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, NPC deputy Fang Zhaoxiang, deputy secretary of Anhui
Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) who
takes charge of agricultural affairs, said his province has for
the second time taken the lead in extending all farmers contract
farmland for another 30 years after the central government set
forth the policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
