<HEADLINE> Postma, Niemann-Stirnemann Break World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEERENVEEN, Netherlands, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Ids Postma of the
Netherlands and Gunda Niemann-Stirnemann of Germany rewrote the
listed world records en route to defending their world titles at
the 1998 World All-Round Speedskating Championships.
</P>
<P>
Postma garnered 153.367 points from four races of 500, 5,000,
1,500 and 10,000 meters for the new world mark while
Niemann-Stirnemann totalled 163.020 points to shatter her own
world mark of 165.708.
</P>
<P>
The previous world mark for men was 155.966 held by Japan's
Keiji Shirahata.
</P>
<P>
Niemann-Stirnemann also bettered the 3,000-meter race world
record during Saturday's competition.
</P>
<P>
Postma clocked 36.48 seconds for 500 meters, 6 minutes 33.09
seconds for 5,000 meters, 1:48.85 for 1,500 meters and 13:45.91
for 10,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Niemann-Stirnemann was timed 40.57 for 500 meters, 1:58.69 for
1,500 meters, 4:05.08 for 1,500 meters (world record time) and
7:00.41 for 5,000 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
