<HEADLINE> Postma, Niemann Retake World All-Round Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEERENVEEN, Netherlands, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Ids Postma of
the Netherlands and Gunda Niemann-Stirnemann of Germany
successfully defended their world number one spots on Sunday as
they won the World All-Round Speedskating Championships both with
new world records.
</P>
<P>
Postma accummulated 153.367 points to win the men's all-round
title while Niemann-Stirnemann posted 163.020 points to take the
women's for a fourth consecutive time and a record seventh
altogether.
</P>
<P>
Niemann-Stirnemann, 31 and oldest woman competitor here, was
ninth in the 500 meters with a clocking of 40.57 seconds, but
finished atop in all the other events by clocking 1 minute 58.69
seconds for 1,500 meters, a world record time of 4:05.08 for
3,000 meters and 7:00.41 for 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
She said that she would continue competing for as long as she
enjoys skating but that she was not sure whether she would
compete in the individual speedskating worlds scheduled to be
held in Calgary, Canada, from March 27 to 29.
</P>
<P>
Women all-rounders raced in four distances also over three
days.
</P>
<P>
Postma finished first in shorter races and fourth in the
longest distance, clocking 36.48 seconds for 500 meters, 6:33.09
for 5,000 meters, 1:48.85 for 1,500 meters and 13:45.91 for
10,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Rintje Ritsma also from hosts the Netherlands finished
runner-up on 154.091 points while Italy's Roberto Sighel was
third on 155.830 points.
</P>
<P>
Claudia Pechstein and Anni Friesinger came in second and third
to complete a German clean-sweep in women's contest. Pechstein
scored 163.669 points while Friesinger got 166.014 points from
the four races.
</P>
<P>
Only the top 12 skaters from the previous three races competed
in Sunday's final events of men's 10,000 meters and women's 5,000
meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
