<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Tridex '98, an international military exhibition,
was opened in Abu Dhabi on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 firms from around the world displayed their most
up-to-date equipment of electronic warfare, communication,
training and medical support services.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Sona Trac, Algeria's national oil company, forecast
the oil output of the North African country would reach 1.4
million barrels per day by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The company also expected Algeria's output of hydrocarbonate
to arrive at 200 million tonnes that year, against 182 million
tonnes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has a proven reserve of 115 billion barrels of
hydrocarbonate.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to export 60 billion cubic meters of natural gas
and 9 million tonnes of liquefied gas in the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's trade deficit rose to 28.6 billion Egyptian
pounds (8.41 billion dollars) in the first 11 months of 1997,
against 28.24 billion pounds (8.31 billion dollars) in the same
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Egypt's annual inflation rate
dropped to 4 percent in 1997 from 5.4 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Russia signed two agreements on Friday,
under which the two countries will promote cooperation in tourism
and banking sector, the official National News Agency reported.
</P>
