<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session in Eyes of a Staffer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A welcome change has occurred in
the National People's Congress (NPC), China's highest legislative
body, said Guo Yongqing, who has served as a bulletin editor for
eight straight years.
</P>
<P>
During the First Session of the Ninth National People's
Congress (NPC) in session here since early March, he can no longer
found any quiet "meeting sitters", in reference to any deputies
who just listen to others speak and do not utter a word themselves
during panel discussions, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
"When I worked for the NPC session for the first time in 1991,"
he recalled, "I felt at ease with my job since quite a number of
deputies simply do not speak at NPC panel discussions."
</P>
<P>
"But I was extremely busy in recent years, because a growing
number of deputies vied with each other to air their views and my
workload became increasing heavy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Guo sends recorded speeches of his delegation member to the
conference bulletin editing center before 11:00 PM every day. And
then its editing staff will print these speeches at night and hand
them out to every NPC delegation early next morning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he acknowledged, there has also been a drastic
change with regard to the contents of deputies' speeches.
</P>
<P>
"During the Seventh NPC session, one third of the deputies
briefed the session merely on the general situation of their own
work units and few related the work of their units to the
government work report submitted for discussion," Guo said.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas at the current session, all deputies, including those
from among workers and farmers, have focused their attention on
such heated topics as institutional restructuring, development of
China's central and western regions and supervision over the
implementation of state laws," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Guo also pointed to an interesting change in the
opening remarks of deputies.
</P>
<P>
In the past, many began their talks with the remark, "I've come
here for the sole purpose of learning from my fellow deputies,"
and the word "learning" was used with the highest frequency.
</P>
<P>
Today, the introductory remarks have changed a great deal. Some
deputies started by simply saying, "I'll say something on behalf
of the people," while some others would say, "I want to make some
proposals" before elaborating on their main topics. A number of
impetuous deputies hit home right on the theme, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the mood in NPC session, changes have also been
reflected in the voices of deputies and looks on their faces. Guo
recalled that seven years ago, many read their prepared speeches
meticulously and in a solemn manner.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he added, "the ongoing session is alive with an
enthusiastic atmosphere with repeated applause and laughters," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Previously, when senior officials from government departments
come to join in panel discussions, deputies would discuss issues
in the related fields they take charge. For instance, if an
official from the Ministry of Fiance came, provincial and local
financial officials would naturally dwell on the relevant finance
topics, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, even with the presence of the above mentioned
officials, deputies from China's rural areas may still deal with
financial matters while deputies who represent entrepreneurs, too,
can set forth proposals or suggestions on agricultural
development.
</P>
<P>
The three reasons behind these changes, Guo said, are that NPC
deputies have a stronger sense of involvement in administration
and discussion of state affairs, NPC sessions have become more
democratic, and the market economy has helped broaden the vision
of NPC deputies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes EU Foreign Ministers' Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government has
welcomed a Saturday agreement reached among European Union (EU)
foreign ministers on terms for opening accession negotiations with
Cyprus as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides commented on a local
private TV Sunday that the EU foreign ministers' accord helps
Cyprus overcome yet another barrier toward a smooth start of
accession negotiations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The informal EU foreign ministers' meeting in Edinburgh
unanimously decided that Cyprus-EU accession talks will begin as
scheduled, on March 31, even if Turkish Cypriots reject an offer
to join the Cyprus government's negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that accession negotiations will eventually
act as a leverage to make Turkey curb its intransigent stand,
which has reached its highest levels, and open the road for
Cyprus' reunification," Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that any retrogression or sign of weakness on the
part of the EU in using this leverage "would harm the interests of
the EU itself."
</P>
<P>
When commenting on the recent statements by Diego Cordovez, the
U.N. chief's special advisor for Cyprus, that the island's
accession course in a way complicates a Cyprus settlement,
Kasoulides expressed his disagreement.
</P>
<P>
"What the Security Council should do is to remain firm to its
decision that the direct peace talks on Cyprus should start from
the point they stopped in Glion, Switzerland, last August," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations between two
Cypriot communities' leaders were held last summer in U.S. and
Switzerland respectively, but they ended in failure due to Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash's refusal of further negotiations
following a EU decision to start accession talks with the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash announced recently that the Turkish Cypriots will not
participate in the U.N.-led peace negotiations and Cyprus'
accession talks with the EU unless his breakaway state is
recognized.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared the breakaway Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus in 1983, which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third of the
island following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have mainly failed in
their peace efforts in the past 24 years for reuniting the divided
island as a bizonal, bicommunal federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
