<HEADLINE> 47 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 47 rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in the military
operations staged by the Turkish security forces over the past
three days in southeastern Turkey, an official statement said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the office of the Emergency Regional
Rule said that the security forces started the air and ground
military operations against the PKK militants in the Besteler and
Dereler regions of Sirnak province bordering Iraq on March 12.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three PKK rebels were killed during the first two-day
clashes between the government troops and the PKK guerrillas in
the regions, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It added that 24 PKK militants more had been shot dead in the
armed clashes in the same regions on Saturday evening and Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
However, three soldiers of the security also died in the
clashes over the past three days, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly called on the international community to
ban the PKK activities and accused neighboring countries of
deliberately aiding the outlawed organization.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war for
autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey, which has claimed
over 28,000 lives since August 1984.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Erkal Bektas from Turkey's General Staff accused some
countries, especially Russia, Syria, Iran, Iraq, Greece and Cyprus
of "continuous support to the PKK".
</P>
<P>
He said that "despite Ankara's massive efforts to curb the
terrorists activities, these countries have been supporting the
PKK".
</P>
<P>
Some 2,500 or 3,000 PKK militants, who have sheltered
themselves in northern Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War, often cross
into the Turkish territory from northern Iraq and attack military
and civilian targets in Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
