<HEADLINE> Additional 150,000 Beijing Households to Use Natural Gas in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- About 150,000 Beijing households
will give up coal and begin using natural gas this year, pushing
the number of natural gas users in the capital to 700,000
households, or one-third of the city's total population, according
to Beijing's Public Utility Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's gas sources could not meet the demand for Beijing's
rapid development in recent years. More than 100,000 families are
waiting to hook up with natural gas every year.
</P>
<P>
Last September, natural gas from northwest China's Shaanxi and
Gansu provinces and Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region was transported
to Beijing. By the end of the year, more than 550,000 Beijing
households had become natural-gas users.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing's Public Utility Bureau, more than 700
million cubic meters of natural gas will be transported to Beijing
from northwest China in 2000. And, by that time, Beijing's
natural-gas users will increase to one million households.
</P>
<P>
Seven hundred million cubic meters of natural gas can replace
1.8 million tons of coal, experts said, adding that the annual
emission of sulphur dioxide and dust will be reduced by 27,000
tons and 21,000 tons, respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Co. to Launch Fund for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A Swiss financial co., Trigone
Capital Finance, will this May launch an investment fund for
Africa to mobilize investment capital into the continent's least
developed countries, the Zimbabwean News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The fund is an outcome of a seminar organized by the U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) and the U.N.
Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO) last year to mobilize
the private sector to encourage foreign investment into least
developed countries on the continent.
</P>
<P>
In its latest newsletter released here Sunday, UNCTAD said the
fund to be known as the Global African Development Fund (GLAD)
would start with an initial capital of 20 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The objective of GLAD, UNCTAD said, would be capital
appreciation over the medium to long term for investment in
traded debts and stocks with 15 percent of its net asset going
toward direct investment in small enterprises on the continent.
</P>
<P>
''For its part, UNCTAD will encourage its member states to
submit investment projects through their investment promotion
agencies,'' the U.N. agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
