<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appointment of Israel's New Mossad Deputy Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua)-- As officially approved by
Israeli cabinet here on Sunday, Northern Commander of Israel
Defense Force (IDF) Maj.-Gen. Amiram Levine has become the deputy
director of Mossad.
</P>
<P>
Mossad is Israel's state intelligence and spy organization.
</P>
<P>
Levine was born in 1946 at Kibbutz Lahavot-Habashan. He
enlisted in the IDF in 1965 and served in the elite Sayeret
Matkal reconnaissance unit during the Six Day War, and was its
deputy commander during the Yom Kippur War, when he was
wounded. After the war, he became its commander.
</P>
<P>
During the war in Lebanon, Levine commanded a tank battalion
and was again wounded during the invasion of Beirut, the Lebanese
capital.
</P>
<P>
He later commanded a tank brigade and an armored division in
the Northern Command and also served as the Northern Command's
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
Levine was appointed Northern Commander in 1994 by then IDF
chief of staff Ehud Barak, who is now head of the Israel's
opposition Labor party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
