<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Emphasizes Family Planning, Environmental Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- China must attach great
importance to family planning and environmental protection upon
which are based economic development, social progress and people's
happy lives, Chinese Premier Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), made the remarks at the meeting on family planning and
environmental protection held here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders Jiang Zemin, Zhu Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao,
Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The departments of family planning and environmental protection
have not been weakened but strengthened in the ongoing State
Council restructuring drive, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The State Council's restructuring will cut almost half of the
State Council's departments to raise government efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the move shows the central government is paying
great attention to family planning and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
"China will go a long way and must work arduously to implement
its family planning policy, and no slight change will be allowed
to this fundamental policy which will keep focusing on rural and
migrating populations," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The family planning work should adapt itself to the market
economy, gradually making most people consciously adopt the means
of contraception, Li said, stressing that scientific research
should be strengthened to develop and spread contraceptive means
and medicine, which are scientific and convenient to use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Emphasizes Family Planning, Environmental Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As to environmental protection, Li said that equal attention
should be paid to both the prevention and treatment of
environmental pollution and the protection of the ecology, which
are of great significance for sustainable development and for
future generations. Governments at all levels should strive to do
a good job in environmental protection while trying to develop
local economies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the governments should give priorities to the
environmental protection drive, stepping up pollution treatment
efforts in key regions and river valleys. The Huaihe River Valley
had initially reached its goal of all industrial polluting sources
meeting discharge standards early last year.
</P>
<P>
All industrial polluting sources in the Taihu Lake Valley
should reach discharge standards this year, with water-pollution
treatment efforts to be stepped up in the Liaohe and Haihe rivers,
Chaohu and Dianchi valleys, he said.
</P>
<P>
A group of obsolete resource- and energy-consumed or seriously
polluting equipment should be eliminated in the economic
restructuring drive, Li said, adding that companies which exceed
pollution standards and have no hope of being treated should be
closed down without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
Financial input should be increased for the development of
science and technology in the field of environmental protection,
he emphasized, adding that attention should be paid to the
adoption and application of technological fruits to rapidly
develop the environmental protection industry.
</P>
<P>
The state has formulated a large number of laws and regulations
concerning environmental protection, and focus should be shifted
to law enforcement, Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the meeting were Peng Peiyun, State Councillor
and minister of the State Family Planning Commission, and Song
Jian, State Councillor and head of the Environmental Protection
Committee of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Leading provincial officials in charge of family planning and
environmental protection attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Issues Top NPC Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Activities of the ongoing session
of China's top law-making body show that Chinese lawmakers are
paying greater attention to the protection of resources,
environment and ecology amid rapid economic development.
</P>
<P>
A common understanding reached by lawmakers and high-ranking
officials alike is that China must make concerted efforts to
protect the environment and natural resources and curb a worsening
of the environment.
</P>
<P>
According to officials handling motions for the First Session
of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), the current session
has received 830 motions, more than 120 of which concern
legislation on resources and environmental protection, next only
to economic matters in number.
</P>
<P>
The biggest number of motions calls for accelerated legislation
to bring under control pollution in rivers such as the Yangtze,
the Yellow river and the Huaihe river and put an end to ecological
worsening and soil erosion in the upper reaches of the Yellow
River and the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Air quality in cities is another concern among NPC deputies.
Many motions call for amendment to relevant laws to minimize
pollution from cars and coal burning. Many other motions concern
the construction of nature reserves and the protection of water
resources, energy, farming environment, and marine resources.
</P>
<P>
A hightened environmental awareness has also been evident at
group discussions attended by NPC deputies.
</P>
<P>
Liu Benren, an NPC deputy, said: "The drying up of the Yellow
River in its lower section and serious pollution of the Huaihe
River have sounded alarm to the whole nation."
</P>
<P>
Li, who is also the boss of the Wuhan Iron and Steel Group,
urged prompt action to protect water resources in and along the
Yangtze to bring a clean river into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The entrepreneur, together with managers of more than 30 large
enterprises, advocated clean production to minimize discharge of
polluting materials and industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Li Bo from Inner Mongolia put forward a proposal, urging
the central government to make resources and environmental
protection an important yardstick for assessing the performance of
officials.
</P>
<P>
Deputies expressed appreciation that, in his government work
report, Premier Li Peng for the first time says environmental
protection is to receive top priority for state funding in the
future, on a par with agriculture, forestry, water conservancy,
energy, transport and telecoms.
</P>
<P>
"This speaks of the determination of the government to protect
environment, ecology and resources and to pursue sustainable a
development," a deputy said.
</P>
<P>
In a discussion with deputies from Beijing, Li Peng reiterated
the importance of environmental protection, urging local
governments to put environmental protection on their work agenda
as an important item.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji at a group discussion called for
stopping tree cutting.
</P>
<P>
"People should become tree planters instead of tree cutters to
create happiness for our future generations," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
