<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Officials Support Financial Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Some local officials attending
the ongoing session of China's top legislature as deputies say
they will not set obstacles for reform of the country's financial
system to protect local interests.
</P>
<P>
The new round of financial reform will free commercial banks
from being a coffer for central and local governments and enable
them to decide what projects to finance purely on the basis of
economic merits.
</P>
<P>
Under the former central planning system, bank loans tended to
go where the government directed, and local economies relied too
much on bank loans, which resulted in a rise of bad loans and poor
fund circulation for all the major state-owned banks.
</P>
<P>
Local officials concur that, without reform, banks will
continue to suffer from such problems, nor will they be able to
play their role as economic regulators.
</P>
<P>
With the market playing an increasingly important role in other
aspects of the economy, banks should likewise meet the needs of a
market economy, says Chai Songyue, Governor of Zhejiang province.
</P>
<P>
Instead of cutting off sources of funding for local economic
development, bank commercialization will instill new vitality into
further economic growth, he says.
</P>
<P>
"With less government interferences," Chai explains,"banks
will be able to provide loans in accordance with market rules,
thus helping to improve the economic structure."
</P>
<P>
Zhou Gongshun, deputy Party chief of Anqing city of Anhui
province, explains that commercialized banks will help prevent
redundant construction by financing only promising projects and
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He admits that it will take some time for governments and
banks to get accustomed to a new financial system.
</P>
<P>
According to Liang Guangda, Party chief of Zhuhai city in
Guangdong province, reform will help foster a good financial
environment.
</P>
<P>
"Well-run businesses won't lack bank loans, while the
government's responsibilities are to build an investment
environment and better serve businesses," he says.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Gang, governor of the Guangdong branch of the People's
Bank of China, the central bank, points out that reform also
requires commercial banks to set up a whole set of control systems
and to operate in accordance with financial laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Reform measures taken in the last few years have laid a
foundation for ongoing fundamental changes, he adds. "Government
interference in bank operation is getting less and less, and a
modern financial system in line with a socialist market economy is
taking shape gradually," he says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
