<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heartland of Arctic Polluted, Scientists find </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The industrial pollutants have
penetrated into the heartland of the Arctic region, researchers
said here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the heavy metal element lead contained
in snow in the heartland of the Arctic Circle was caused by
industrial pollution, a group of Chinese scientists announced in a
new issue of Chinese Science Bulletin published today.
</P>
<P>
The research, conducted by a group with the Lanzhou Institute
of Glaciology and Cryopedology under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, also showed that lead pollution in the North Pole area
comes mainly from Eastern Europe, the central and far eastern
portions of Russia and western part of North America.
</P>
<P>
"Two air masses reaching the Arctic Ocean may be the main
source for the pollution," a researcher said.
</P>
<P>
The first air mass comes from Eastern Europe and central Russia
where industrial pollution is concentrated. The second air mass
brings pollutants from North America and Russia's far east region.
</P>
<P>
The study indicates that the lead isotopes in the heartland of
the Arctic matches that of the Eastern Europe and the western part
of North America, scientists noted.
</P>
<P>
"Such heavy metal elements as lead in snow is often used by
scientists as an indicator for air circulation, which
comprehensively reflects the time and intensity of pollution," a
researcher explained.
</P>
<P>
So far, according to researchers, scientific data on lead in
the heartland of the Arctic are very rare.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the research was based on snow samples
taken by China's first Arctic scientific expedition team in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Extremely strict pollution-preventing measures were taken
during the sampling, scientists said, and the whole laboratory
test process was conducted under an extremely clean environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0073 </DOCNO>
