<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Reviews Security Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet reviewed
Sunday the past week of violent clashes in the West Bank, calling
on Jewish settlers to avoid more violence.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who chaired the weekly
Cabinet session, said the worsening situation in the West Bank
was caused by the killing of three Palestinian workers by Israeli
soldiers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu demanded the settlers living in the divided
flashpoint city Hebron obey orders from the Army and not take the
law into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on Friday night's violent clash between
settlers and Palestinian residents in Hebron when the settlers
entered the Palestinian-ruled areas to stage protests. Seventeen
people, including eight Palestinian journalists, were injured by
rubber bullets fired by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Hebron's Israeli police intended to question several settlers
who led the Friday protest. The protest organizers claimed that
the settlers were not properly protected by the soldiers and they
decided to stage the protest after shots were fired at a Jewish
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army's Chief of Staff Lipkin Amnon Shahak toured
Hebron Sunday morning, as officers defended the soldiers against
the charges by Hebron settlers. Division commander of Israeli
troops in the West Bank Yitzhak Eitan said the Friday clash in
Hebron was provoked by the settlers. He added that there was full
cooperation between Israeli troops and Palestinian police in
quelling the rioting.
</P>
<P>
Following five days of widespread violent clashes, in which
dozens of Palestinians have been wounded, the situation in the
West Bank was relatively calm on Sunday. However, Israeli
security forces remained on high alert against new violence.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of three bombings in some Israeli cities in the
past days, Israeli police across the country were also put on
high alert against possible bigger terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a small explosion occurred outside the Old City in
East Jerusalem, injuring four Palestinians. Saturday evening, a
man in the northern town Afula lost his both hands in an
explosion at the central bus station.
</P>
<P>
Sunday morning, police in the coastal city Netanya tried to
determine whether a small explosion that blew off a youth's hand
in a nightclub was a terror attack. The young man claimed that
the bomb was hidden in a bag that he found outside the club and
brought inside.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police are suspecting that Palestinian militants are
launching a new wave of terror attacks that is different from the
past. In the past, Palestinian terrorists usually launched
suicide bombings in crowded areas in Israel, inflicting heavy
casualties.
</P>
<P>
But as Israel has beefed up security around the country and
made it more difficult to perpetrate suicide bombings, police
believed that the terrorists have changed tactics by using
smaller bombs to cause massive disruptions in public
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
