<HEADLINE> S. African Ministers to Visit Mozambique on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A top-level South African
Ministerial delegation is to visit Mozambique this week to
discuss the arrest of a South African foreign affairs department
official for alleged arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has asked the Mozambican
government for an urgent meeting to discuss the arrest of Robert
Mcbride, expected on Tuesday, the Sunday Independent reported.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi and Deputy
Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad are to meet the Mozambican interior
minister, Mufamadi's office was quoted as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decision that the government would approach the Mozambican
authorities directly was taken after a lengthy meeting Friday
involving Mufamadi, Pahad and members of the intelligence
services.
</P>
<P>
Mcbride, a deputy director on the Asian desk in the Foreign
Affairs Department, was arrested Monday in Mozambique's border
town Ressano Garcia for alleged illegal arms dealing.
</P>
<P>
During a visit by his wife and South African high commissioner
to Mozambique Mangisi Zitha Friday, Mcbride reportedly denied
smuggling weapons to South Africa or any other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said he had gone to investigate gun smuggling on his own
initiative and was sorry for embarrassing the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, South African and the ruling African National
Congress (ANC) officials had distanced themselves from Mcbride,
saying he was on an unauthorized private visit to Mozambique at
the time of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
They said the Mozambican law should take its course in the
matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
