<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Privately Run Companies Eye Infrastructure (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show that, by the end of 1997, China had more than
28 million self-employed businesses with registered capital of 250
billion yuan and 800,000 private companies involving six million
employees and registered capital of 340 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
They are mostly engaged in commerce, trade and processing
industries.
</P>
<P>
In the present-day buyer's market, however, the processing
sector witnesses fierce competitiveness, low profit rate and high
risk rate.
</P>
<P>
But infrastructure investment seems to have a higher and more
stable profit picture.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure has long been the bottleneck of China's economic
development. There is an investment-hunger in this field because
the government cannot afford to invest all by itself while foreign
investors seldom venture into the area.
</P>
<P>
An opportunity is thus left for privately run companies to
exploit this untapped field.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has stipulated a comparatively loose
policy on such enterprises to help them re-choose what to do after
they had summed up enough capital from commercial, trade and
processing activities.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China,
which was held last September, offered more opportunities for
these enterprises. A report delivered at the meeting stated that
the private-run economy is an important part of the socialist
market economy. Many local governments have stipulated regulations
accordingly that allowed these enterprises to expand their
businesses into more areas.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that, with looser control over the private
enterprises, they will surely branch into more investment fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Privately Run Companies Eye Infrastructure (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Three farmers in east China's
Shandong Province have invested 12 million yuan to build a
630-meter railway as part of a trend toward private investment in
building infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more and more private-run firms have shifted
their arena from commerce, trade, and processing industry to
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The Mingliu Company in Quanzhou, a city in east China's Fujian
province, has invested 250 million yuan in building a 1,530-meter
bridge across the Jinjiang River. The bridge was put into
operation a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In another case, the Rongbin Group in Xiamen, a city in Fujian
Province, has decided to invest 200 million yuan to build a bridge
across the Xiangjiang River in Changsha, capital of central
China's Hunan Province. To date, one-third of the investment has
been completed.
</P>
<P>
"It is a trend for private-run enterprises to invest in
infrastructure," said Li Ding, director of the Society of Chinese
Private-run Economy. He said that infrastructures should become
the major industry for some private-run companies.
</P>
<P>
In China, the private-run economy involves rural companies,
share-holding enterprises in which the state has no stake,
private-owned enterprises and the self-employed, according to Tong
Dalin, deputy director of the Society of China's Restructuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
