<HEADLINE> Syria, Lebanon Reject Conditional Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Syria and Lebanon have declared
their rejection of any conditioned Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
This came during Saturday's meeting here between Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad and his Lebanese counterpart Elias
Hrawi. The meeting coincided with the 20th anniversary of the
issue of the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 which calls for
Israeli troops withdrawal from south Lebanon without delay.
</P>
<P>
Both sides insisted on not having talks or meetings with the
Israeli side, and on giving no guarantees in return for an Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon, stressing that the U.N. resolution
should be carried out without any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Israel has proposed to withdraw from south Lebanon to exchange
for Lebanon's security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that the Damascus summit drew
up a joint strategy stressing the inseparability of the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks of the Middle East peace process, the two
countries' commitment to the overall and fair peace option and the
land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Lebanese summit came just a week before the arrival
of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in Lebanon within a Mideast
tour, that will take him to Egypt, Israel, Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi arrived here Saturday for an official visit to Syria.
</P>
</TEXT>
