<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Kills 15 Armed Infiltrators in C. Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan army killed 15 armed
infiltrators in Kayenzi Commune of Central Gitarama prefecture
Friday morning, radio Rwanda, monitored here, reported in Kigali
late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Army spokesman Major Emmanuel Ndahiro confirmed the report and
indicated that 10 assault rifles were also seized. There was also
many casualties among the infiltrators, he said.
</P>
<P>
''The operation in which the infiltrators were killed followed
tips by local residents who had learned about the attack,''
Ndahiro told Rwanda News Agency (RNA) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan military official expressed satisfaction about the
high level of collaboration between the residents of Gitarama and
security forces which helped to rout out about 3,000 armed Hutu
insurgents who raided some communes, north of Gitarama town.
</P>
<P>
''In some cases, local residents netted infiltrators, disarmed
them, and handed them over to the authorities,'' security sources
in Gitarama said.
</P>
<P>
This was the case in Nyakabanda commune where the local
population arrested 11 armed infiltrators and handed them to a
nearby military post.
</P>
<P>
On February 28, about 3,000 armed Hutu insurgents had attacked
the communes of Bulinga, Nyakabanda, Rutobwe, and Nyabikenke in
Central Rwanda from neighboring southern Gisenyi prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Following the intervention of the army, the infiltrators
scattered in hills and swamps of the region.
</P>
<P>
This led to ongoing mop-up operations in which the population
is playing an important role.
</P>
<P>
Security forces in Gitarama announced Thursday that an
adjutant of the former Rwandan government forces (ex-FAR) was
among the infiltrators captured in such operations.
</P>
<P>
A notorious commander of the armed infiltrators code-named
''Ninja'' was also killed in clashes, the RNA claimed in a
special dispatch to Xinhua Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Some e-FAR soldiers and the notorious ''Interahamwe''
militiamen are behind the waves of violence in northwestern
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
According to revelations by those captured in the fighting,
the raid on Central Rwanda was just an adventure.
</P>
<P>
Military analysts say that these raids were triggered by
intense pressure exerted on them by the Rwandan army in the
northwest and serious logistical problems relating to food
shortages, and the growing anger of the population which was
weary of their terror.
</P>
<P>
Some of the infiltrators captured affirmed that it was out of
desperation that they launched the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
