<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) gathered in Qatar's
capital Doha Sunday morning to discuss international issues
related to the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
The gathering will last for five days and the foreign
ministers, joined by Palestinian President Yasser Arafat and
leaders of other regional Arab groups, will discuss Islamic issues
around the world, the official Qatar news agency (QNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The issues mainly include the stalled Arab-Israeli peace
process, the situation in Iraq in light of the recent agreement
between Baghdad and the United Nations on arms inspections and
Libya's strained ties with western countries.
</P>
<P>
The participants will also focus their discussions on violent
disputes between Muslims and Serbs in Bosnia-Herzegovina and
Kosovo province of Serbia, and the current situation in
Afghanistan, as well as the territorial dispute between Pakistan
and India on Kashmir, QNA said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers' meeting followed the eighth OIC summit
held in Tehran, Iran last December.
</P>
<P>
The previous OIC meeting of foreign ministers was held in
Jakarta, Indonesia from December 9 to 13 in 1996. 
