<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. Bank to Offer $480m Loan to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is to offer 480
million U.S. Dollars loan to help Mozambique develop its basic
infrastructure and personnel training and private sector during
the three years between 1998 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
Domingo, a Sunday paper published here Sunday quoted James
Coates, the bank representative to Mozambique as saying that the
sum has doubled the figure during the 1995-97 period.
</P>
<P>
Coates said the decision for the new loan was made in response
to the rapid developing economy and infrastructure in Mozambique,
and a support for the country's agriculture, education and
industry.
</P>
<P>
The pre-condition for the loan, according to the World Bank,
is a stable macro-economy, a policy framework backing
agricultural investment and a continued policy of privatizing
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank provides the loan to support Mozambique in
carrying out its three development corridors of Maputo, Beira and
Nacala in southern, central and northern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Mozambique and Uganda have become examples
of good economies in Africa. By the end of last year, Mozambique
had registered a growth rate of six to eight percent, and an
inflation rate of six percent, the lowest in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has offered the country more than one billion
U.S. Dollars in 30 loans since 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
