<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cities Mark International Consumers' Rights Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Major Chinese cities have
announced new measures to handle an increasing number complaints
by consumers of the country.
</P>
<P>
A consumer complaint network went into operation today in
Xiamen, one of the country's four Special Economic Zones in east
China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The complaint network covers seven branches of the city's
Bureau for industry and Commerce and 35 local industrial and
commercial offices with a special telephone number: 96315.
</P>
<P>
The aim of establishing the network is to protect consumers'
rights, fight against the production and sale of fake and shoddy
goods, commercial fraud and various economic criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, more than 100 department stores established a new
method called "fair balance" to protect the rights and interest of
consumers. The method will be introduced to all local department
stores and chain stores within the year, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Chongqing Municipality has established a
special court to protect the legitimate rights and interests of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
Related regulations have been worked out to standardize trials
in consumer cases.
</P>
<P>
Other cities such as Beijing, Shijiazhuang and Jinan have all
opened similar telephone hot lines to handle consumer's complaints
or have established service centers.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, over the past decade China has passed more than a
dozen national laws and regulations designed to protect consumers'
rights in addition to similar regulations adopted by provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
This year, the State Administration for Industry and Commerce
is focusing its attention on protecting the rights of consumers in
rural areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
