<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Promote Tourist Attractions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- About 40 Southern African
companies will this week market their tourist attractions at a
three-day convention to be held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, South
African Press Association reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This platform would for the first time be open to all
countries in the region, and not only South Africa, said Southern
African Travel Mart (SATM) General Manager BP Tan.
</P>
<P>
The SATM, which runs from Monday to Wednesday, would see
Southern African countries promoting themselves as tourist
destinations among 70 buyer companies from Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Hotels, game lodges, nature reserves, tours, and coach or car
hire services are among the attractions to be marketed. Countries
to be represented included South Africa, Malawi, Mauritius,
Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
South Africa gained about 1.26 billion Rand (252 million U.S.
Dollars) in tourism income from Far East Asia and the Middle East
between January and August last year.
</P>
<P>
From January to September, 103,238 Asian nationals visited
South Africa, out of a total of more than four million tourists
to the country, according to South Africa Tourism Board figures.
</P>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur was reportedly positioning itself as an Asian
travel hub. Malaysia is the second largest investor in South
Africa (1.8 billion Rand in 1996). Its investments were mainly
concentrated in property development and the tourism industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
