<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President to Visit U.S. Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
will soon pay a visit to the U.S. for talks with President Bill
Clinton on propelling the Mideast peace process and boosting
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ambassador in Washington Ahmed Meher was quoted in
local newspaper Al-Akhbar as saying Sunday that the date of the
visit will be set through contacts between the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
Meher confirmed an Egyptian proposal on cutting down its
20-year use of U.S. aid, saying Egypt draws up a working paper on
the alternatives of reducing the aid and will forward it to the
U.S. administration soon.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt reckons the U.S. aid could not continue forever," he
said, adding that the aid helped construct Egypt's infrastructure
projects and enabled the American companies to carry out projects
outside the U.S..
</P>
<P>
In a related development, U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Daniel
Kurtzer said earlier that the suggested reduction of U.S. aid to
Egypt goes in line with the success of Cairo's economic reform
program.
</P>
<P>
"The economic aid had fulfilled its aims during the past
phase," the U.S. diplomat told a press conference here last
Thursday. He said talks on cutting down aid allocated to Egypt
will start within five months.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has proposed to the Clinton administration to reduce the
annual 815-million dollar economic aid it gets from Washington,
before Israel presented a plan to cut the economic aid it receives
from the U.S. in return for increasing the military assistance.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Israel receive annual American military and economic
aid after signing a U.S.-brokered peace deal in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Washington promised to allocate 2.1 billion dollars for Egypt
in 1998 and 3 billion dollars for Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aid has been more a controversial topic than a welcome
one for the Egyptian public who fear that the U.S. aid has exposed
the innermost information of the Egyptian society to America and
accelerated its economic dependence on the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aid has infiltrated into almost every economic sector
in Egypt, providing grants even to the People's Assembly and Shura
Council themselves.
</P>
<P>
If the aid is cut off, the government should seize the chance
to adopt a new approach of greater self-reliance in implementing
economic development projects, said some legislators.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economic assistance to Egypt amounted to 21 billion
dollars between 1975 and 1996. It used to take the forms of
repayable loans and unrepayable grants before most of it was
offered as grants since 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
