<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Elders Accuse U.S. of Interference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Elders in northern Nigeria have
accused the U.S. of interfering in Nigeria's internal affairs by
trying to dictate who should emerge as the west Africa country's
civilian president in August.
</P>
<P>
A statement to this effect was issued Saturday in Kaduna by
the Northern Elders Forum, following the remark made by the U.S.
Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs that the
election of Nigeria's military leader, General Sani Abacha would
be unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
"It is sheer double standards typical of the United States of
America to oppose the candidature of a career military officer to
seek an elective office in Nigeria while at the same time
lobbying General Collin Powell, the retired Chairman, Joint
Chiefs of Staff of the American Armed Forces to seek
nomination... during the 1996 American presidential election,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to General Abacha's transition to civil rule
program, a civilian government will replace his military
government in October, following a presidential election on
August 1.
</P>
<P>
The question of whether Abacha should contest or not has been
an issue of controversy both within and outside Nigeria, as the
transition program draws to its end.
</P>
<P>
Elders, or traditional rulers have a great influence in
Nigerian politics, while the north has produced most of the
Nigerian leaders since its independence in 1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
