<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Shelters "Wanted" Mobutu Officials: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 120 high-ranking
officials of the former Zairean regime headed by Mobutu Sese Seko
are living in South Africa, local daily the Sunday Independent
quoted a confidential intelligence report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of the 120 Zairean officials, most of whom were senior
soliders or civil servants, 102 are on a "wanted" list issued by
President Laurent Kabila of Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) in
connection with the looting of state coffers.
</P>
<P>
Of the four most wanted by Kabila, three are generals who
arrived in South Africa with two extremely heavy suitcases on an
illegal flight in May last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The former Zairean generals were allegedly carrying diamonds
and millions of U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The presence in South Africa of so many of Mobutu's former
officials, many of whom have dual citizenship along with
property, investments and families in South Africa, was
continuing to cause problems in the relationship between the DRC
and South Africa, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula, the head of the Intelligence
Committee, told a press conference this week that a special task
force was established to look into a number of allegations,
including National Intelligency Agency (NIA) complicity in the
generals' departure from former Zaire, now the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The task force, which visited the DRC twice during its
investigations, was made up of representatives of the NIA, the
South African secret service, the ministry of intelligency, the
departments of foreign and home affairs and the police.
</P>
<P>
As part of its probe, the task force checked the log-sheet of
every flight into South Africa over a period of several months,
verified the details of every passenger and cargo load on those
flights and compiled a list of exiled Zaireans living in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mapisa-Nqakula declined to say how many members of the Mobutu
regime had sought refuge in South Africa. However, she admitted
deficiencies in the border control system, corruption in the
departments of foreign and home affairs, and the low level of
accountability required of NIA and secret service agents under
current legislation.
</P>
<P>
Mapisa-Nqakula said the task team's report "identified
weaknesses in border control, and security measures at some of
the airports were not properly enforced..." There were virtually
no means of effectively monitoring the movement of foreign
nationals.
</P>
<P>
"This has led to some of them exploiting that loophole by
engaging in... illegal activities." However, Mapisa-Nqakula said,
a process of correcting this was under way. She said new
legislation aimed at boosting the accountability of state agents
would be tabled in parliament this year, and the question of
diplomatic immunity would also be examined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
