<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC not to Contest Overturn of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) has said it would not contest a
Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) court bid to overturn
amnesties granted to 37 top ANC officials.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Saturday after a meeting of the ANC's
subcommittee on truth and reconciliation, chaired by Vice
President Thabo Mbeki, the ANC recommitted itself to cooperating
fully with the truth and reconciliation process, City Press paper
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The TRC launched an application on the Cape Town High Court
Friday to overturn the amnesties granted to 37 senior ANC
officials last November by the TRC's amnesty committee, which
enjoys autonomy from the rest of the TRC.
</P>
<P>
Among the 37 are Mbeki, Defense Minister Joe Modise, Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo, Justice Minister Dullah Omar, Transport
Minister Mac Maharaj and Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan.
</P>
<P>
TRC chairman Desmond Tutu said in court papers that the
amnesties were invalid "by virtue of at least four
irregularities", including failure to make full disclosure of the
offenses and to identify specific acts.
</P>
<P>
The ANC said it would try to avoid a situation where the
process is turned into a "political football", adding that it
would approach the court application in a non-adversarial manner.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Party (NP), the country's biggest
opposition party, said Saturday it would not withdraw its own
court bid to overturn the blanket amnesty as requested by the
TRC.
</P>
<P>
The NP launched the action on Thursday, claiming the amnesty
committee had been biased toward the ANC in granting the pardons.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty committee is entitled to pardon those guilty of
human rights crimes provided full disclosure of the offenses is
made and a political motive is proven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
