<HEADLINE> Sprinter Marsh Sets Sights on Commonwealth Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Damien Marsh has set his sights
on this year's Kuala Lumpur Commonwealth Games after winning the
200-meter final at the Australian track and field championships in
Melbourne on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Marsh, who had long been plagued with an
Achilles heel injury, clocked 21.34 seconds to beat teenager
Matt Shirvington after two false starts.
</P>
<P>
Marsh, who came fourth at the last Games in Victoria, Canada,
four years ago, said his aim now was to do better in September's
Commonwealth Games in the Malaysian capital.
</P>
<P>
Shirvington, who won the 100m on Saturday, was second in
21.37 seconds ahead of Patrick Johnson in 21.42.
</P>
<P>
Melinda Gainsford-Taylor dominated the women's 200m final to
win in 22.53 seconds, taking her fifth 100-200m double at national
championships.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere on Sunday, defending champion Kyle Vander Kuyp held
off two fast-finishing Japanese runners to retain his title in 14
seconds flat in the men's 110m hurdle.
</P>
<P>
Olympic high jumper Tim Forsyth cleared 2.32 meters for the
gold while New Zealand's world champion Beatrice Faumuina won the
discus with a throw of 63.80 meters, with Australian Lisa-Marie
Vizaniari taking the silver with 61.41. 
</P>
</TEXT>
