<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Liberalization Should Be Cautiously Pursued: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The pace of liberalization
in key industries, where the capacity of Southeast Asian countries
to compete against global giants was weak, must be carefully
calibrated, Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Notwithstanding what the logic of liberalization might suggest,
national security considerations might require that certain
strategic industries continue to remain in the hands of nationals,
he said in his keynote address at the three-day 8th Southeast Asia
Forum which opened here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said efforts to redress the economic situation in Southeast
Asia must take into account the fundamental security and
well-being of the society.
</P>
<P>
He said prescriptions for recovery, especially those coming
from abroad, rarely factored in this "supreme" consideration as
they were often laden with the logic of pure economics.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the immediate concern now was to restore
confidence in the markets and stabilize exchange rates with
measures such as sound macro-economic policies, improving
corporate and public sector governance and curbing excessive
credit expansion.
</P>
<P>
He said the affected countries in Southeast Asia must be
prepared to subordinate some of their national programs to the
overriding objective of economic rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis has brought ASEAN (Association of Southeast
Asian Nations) members closer and helped to minimize differences
among them, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also touched on the issues such as the illegal
flow of migrants stemming from the economic situation in the
region, the forest fires in the region and the situation in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
On Cambodia, he expressed hope that free and fair elections
would be successfully held there and that all impediments to the
admission of that country into ASEAN would be removed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
