<HEADLINE> Tomba Wins Final Men's Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Alberto Tomba of Italy captured
the final men's slalom of the Alpine Ski World Cup season in Crans
Montana, Switzerlan, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tomba clocked one minute 42.84 seconds for the win. Norway's
Hans-Petter Buraas finished second with 1:42.98 and his compatriot
Finn Christian Jagge third in 1:43.61.
</P>
<P>
This was Tomba's 50th World Cup win and might be the last since
he had announced on Saturday he would retire after the race.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Thomas Sykora took the World Cup slalom title by
finishing above arch-rival Thomas Stangassingerin who had started
the day with a slender 12 point lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
