<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Israeli Compliance With Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook has urged Israel to implement all signed agreements with the
Palestinians to bring the peace process back on track, an Arabic
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Al-Ahram on the occasion of his
Cairo visit slated for Sunday, Cook said that Britain supports
full and unconditional implementation of the Palestinian-Israeli
agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Israel ought to urgently and substantially redeploy its troops
in the West Bank," he added, adding that it is hard to achieve any
progress towards the final stage negotiations due to the "mistrust
between the parties concerned in the region."
</P>
<P>
Cook, starting a tour of the region which brings him to Egypt,
Jordan, Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria and
Lebanon, is carrying a European plan to revive the stalled Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, among other things, calls for Palestinian
commitment to Israel's security demands, and urges Israel to
implement a significant troops redeployment and halt settlement
operations. It also urges support to the Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
The British official told the daily that the Middle East peace
process tops Britain's priorities during its tenure as the
rotating chairman of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"Britain pursued, and still, contacts with the parties
concerned, European states and the U.S. to achieve progress in the
peace process in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process have been deadlocked for
nearly a year over Israeli construction of a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem. The U.S. mediation has failed to revive the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Cook described Britain's relations with the Arab world as
"well-grounded" as the two sides have historical land trade links
besides the dialog at political level.
</P>
<P>
Cook also hailed the sound relationship with Egypt, which will
be the first stop of his six-leg tour, and said President Hosni
Mubarak is playing a significant role in maintaining stability in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Talks with the Egyptian leaders will cover the latest
developments in the Middle East and the situation in the occupied
lands especially following the Hebron demonstrations as well as
the Iraq crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between the two countries amounts to 1
billion U.S. dollars annually. Britain is also Egypt's second
largest foreign investor with investments standing at 1 billion
sterlings (1.67 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
