<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striving To Develop Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- China's largest commercial
center, Shanghai, plans to raise its share of the commercial
turnover in the gross domestic product (GDP) mix from 11.4 percent
to 13 percent in three years, said Deputy-Mayor Feng Guoqin.
</P>
<P>
Feng addressed a recent meeting on commerce, saying that retail
sales will increase from last year's 132 billion yuan to 180
billion yuan in 2000 and the operating floor space for retail
business will increase from the present 10 million square meters
to 13 million.
</P>
<P>
He said Shanghai has sustained a 15 percent annual increase in
retail business for five consecutive years in a buyer's
market. However, the competition in prices indicates that the
commercial mix needs to be improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
Feng said that the building of commercial streets in major
residential and downtown areas will be the main focus. Meanwhile,
the city will step up the development of commercial services and
commodity wholesale outlets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
