<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: A Practical Option in Wake of "Soft Landing" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Due to the impact of the recent financial crisis in Southeast
Asia, China's export prospects are rather stark this year, and
apparent sluggish sales are also haunting the country's domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, economists noted, it has become an
inevitable option for the government to resort to expanding
investment demand to help vitalize the market and support
essential economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In fact, conditions are already ripe for an appropriate
increase of investment, as inflation has been reduced to the
minimum level since the beginning of the reform and opening-up
drive two decades ago, they said.
</P>
<P>
Many NPC deputies from the economic circles agree to the
government's decision to continue carrying out the appropriately
tight fiscal and monetary policy, but suggest that this policy be
appropriately readjusted according to new domestic and global
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
They hold that the Chinese economy has accumulated some
strength through its "soft landing", and that various basic
economic factors nowadays are favorable for an investment growth.
</P>
<P>
Money supply will be adequate with a huge national deposit pool
and largely expanded channels of direct financing, stocks and
bonds markets in particular.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, possibilities of a shortage of production means or
consumer goods are very small, which means that investment will
not stimulate inflation; and cheap price of building materials,
equipment and labor has provided a golden opportunity for
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
It has become quite obvious that the Chinese authorities have
decided to place emphasis on economic restructuring and
sustainable development while increasing investment.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts are unanimous that investment in
infrastructure, energy and transportation sectors, industries
supported by high and new technologies and technical upgrading of
enterprises will undoubtedly pave the way for China's future
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, measures like developing urban residential housing
market and stepping up industrialization of the agricultural
sector will expectedly turn people's savings deposits, which have
totaled 5,000 billion yuan and have been expanding by 800 billion
yuan annually, into huge domestic consumption and develop the
potential market in the vast rural areas, they added.
</P>
<P>
In view of the lesson of past economic overheating, they said,
the government will keep a tight control on high-grade real estate
projects and prevent any capital from flowing into areas of
redundant production, just as the top banker Dai warned:
"Resoluted efforts must be made to prevent resurgence of bubble
economy."
</P>
<P>
With the absence of a self-restrainable investment system
guided by the market in China today, a senior official with the
central bank further noted, macro-control departments of the
government must follow closely every move of economic development,
so as to avoid any rapid economic decline or rebound.
</P>
<P>
While it is not easy to achieve high growth and low inflation
for the economy, observers further noted, it will be harder still
to maintain sustained growth after the "soft landing" and with a
buyer's market.
</P>
<P>
"Judging from the current situation, China's decision-makers
have made a truly realistic and wise option," they commented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: A Practical Option in Wake of "Soft Landing" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Although it's still too early to
predict any change the Chinese government will introduce to its
"appropriately tight" fiscal and monetary policy implemented in
recent years, initial signs indicate that this "appropriately
tight" policy tends to be a little more flexible and lenient.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the ongoing session of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), the top legislature, deputies of
all social sectors hold that maintaining an annual economic growth
of no less than eight percent is of vital importance to China's
future development.
</P>
<P>
They also reach consensus that a feasible option for China to
promote its economic growth, which has shown some inclined signs
of cooling down, is to increase investment and expand domestic
demand.
</P>
<P>
At a recent press conference hosted by the current NPC session,
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, said China is expected to increase its overall money supply
by 18 percent this year, two percentage points higher than in the
previous year, and that the investment in fixed assets for 1998
will also increase by 270 billion yuan (32.5 billion US dollars)
and this figure will possibly be higher in the course of
implementation.
</P>
<P>
"An appropriate growth in investment and money supply is aimed
at expanding domestic demand in support of economic growth," the
top banker explained explicitly.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that China's goal of an eight percent economic
growth for 1998 is realistic and feasible, difficulties are still
involved in achieving it, and special attention should be paid to
signs of subsiding slowdown in economic growth, according to a
number of noted figures in the economic circles.
</P>
<P>
A senior analyst with the central bank noted that a sustained
economic growth should move on smoothly at the platform of "soft
landing" and any possible "landslide" should be guarded against at
present, because an economic landslip once occurs, it will exert
an unnegligible negative impact on China's development over the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
In line with China's modernization plan, which prompts the
world's most populous nation to catch up with the
moderately-developed nations in mid next century in terms of
degree of affluency, a fairly-high growth rate should be
maintained in the stage of its economic takeoff.
</P>
<P>
China scored an average annual growth of 11 percent during the
Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995) and, in the past few
years, as a result of macro-control measures over the heated
economy, which reduced the rate of inflation down from 21.7
percent to merely 0.8 percent last year, the country's economic
growth rate was also lowered to 8.8 percent in 1997 from 13.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has decided to seek an average economic
growth of seven to eight percent a year during the Ninth Five-Year
Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
