<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Japan Agree Reforms Need Flexibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Japan Sunday agreed
on the need for flexibility in the implementation of some aspects
of the IMF (International Monetary Fund) program to end the
monetary crisis in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during more than two hours of talks
between visiting Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and
Indonesian President Soeharto here, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed on the importance of the reform
program in Indonesia in cooperation with international financial
institutions based on mutual agreement, said Alatas.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia in mid-January signed a new agreement with the IMF to
carry out sweeping economic reforms in return for an IMF-led
bailout package of more than 40 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan pledged to provide special assistance within the
bilateral framework, apart from the five billion U.S. dollars
worth of loans provided by Japan to the IMF rescue package, Alatas
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say how much Japan promised to give.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral assistance is in the form of providing food and
procurement. Japan also facilitates "trade insurance" for
Indonesian staples importers.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Hashimoto, who arrived here Saturday
evening, expressed his concern over the impact of the current
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also expressed confidence that President
Soeharto would take a brave step to overcome the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Japan says it is still committed to the IMF bailout. Hashimoto
invited Indonesia to establish cooperation with the international
financial institutions and friendly countries in efforts to end
the crisis so that Indonesia could continue its development.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is the first foreign leader to meet Soeharto since he
was re-elected as the Indonesian president for the seventh term.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed Indonesia's problems in
implementing the economic reforms program, such as issues of
foreign debts, the rupiah (national currency) exchange rates
against the U.S. dollar as well as the IMF-plus program (Currency
Board System).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto was due to leave for Tokyo later on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
