<HEADLINE> Nike to Lay Off Workers Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Nike Inc., the world's largest
sports shoe maker, is planning to lay off workers at home and abroad
in the coming weeks, according to reports from Portland, where the
company's headquarters is based.
</P>
<P>
Nike Inc. will cut about 250 employees in Oregan and another 200
elsewhere in the country starting next week, The Oregonian reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The reduction amounts to less than 4 percent of Nike's domestic
workforce of 11,600. Industry sources had estimated the company would
eliminate about 1,500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Nike is expected to announce job reductions overseas on coming
Wednesday, the newspaper said, adding that at least 700 international
employees could be fired.
</P>
<P>
This is the third layoff in recent Nike history. It cut 269 jobs in
1987 and 459 jobs in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Nike spokesman Lee Weinstein said there would be "a
global reduction in force in the course of the next few weeks" because
the Asian financial crisis has been cutting into Nike's profits and
battering its stock.
</P>
<P>
He said Nike was experiencing higher-than-anticipated order
cancellation rates in the Asia Pacific region, and that aggressive
pricing of close-out inventories, particularly in Japan, had hurt
revenues and gross profit margins.
</P>
<P>
Nike has a total of 21,800 employees worldwide by the end of last
year and the company terminated earlier this week 300 temporary
workers, mostly at its headquarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
