<HEADLINE> Chinese Staff Playing Important Role in Foreign Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese staff members are
playing more important roles in foreign agencies registered in
China.
</P>
<P>
Larry Wang, program manager of human resources from Lucent
Technologies (China) Company Ltd., said that working staff members
of his company's personnel department are all Chinese, and the
Chinese manager has the right to select new employees.
</P>
<P>
Wang, born and raised in China, took his current post after
graduation from the enterprise management department of Hubei
Polytechnical University.
</P>
<P>
Foreign agencies registered in the country commonly fill
mid-rank jobs with Chinese employees.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 100 of the 20,000-plus Chinese
staff members in 5,000 foreign agencies in the capital hold posts
of deputy general manager or higher.
</P>
<P>
These Chinese staff members are beneficiaries of the local
human resources strategy of international companies with branches
in China.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Wong, human resources manager for Henkel Asia-Pacific
Ltd., a German company with its China headquarters in Hong Kong,
said that the aim of transnational companies' local policies in
human resources is to show that their investment in China is for
the long haul and not a short-term action.
</P>
<P>
He said the company, which has invested 300 million
U.S. dollars to establish 17 joint ventures in the country's
chemical industry, plans to help Chinese staff members fill at
least 50 percent of the firm's mid- and high-ranking positions
within five years.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign agencies introduced the local policy to save money
on salaries, welfare and housing.
</P>
<P>
Many transnational companies have launched personnel training
programs to train locally hired personnel.
</P>
<P>
Last August, Henkel and Shanghai Communications University
cooperated on a training class. So far, more than 500 people have
attended the class. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
