<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Halt Foreign Exchange Supply to Travelers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government has
decided to stop supplying foreign exchanges to Iranian travelers
due to a reduction of the country's foreign exchange incomes.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Iran News Sunday quoted informed
sources as saying that the country's banking system would not sell
foreign exchanges to Iranian travelers as of the beginning of the
next fiscal year (to start on March 21) until further notice.
</P>
<P>
According to the present regulation, every Iranian traveling
abroad can buy 300 to 1,000 U.S. dollars according to his or her
destination from the banking system with a rate of 3,000 rials
against one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts blame the drop in oil revenues as the main reason
behind the government's move to stop selling foreign exchanges,
Iran News said.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil revenue during the 11 months of the current
fiscal year (to end on March 21) stood at 14.3 billion dollars,
while the government's budget projected an income of 17.7 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of oil revenue has caused a budget deficit of
4.57 billion dollars in the current fiscal year and will raise the
deficit to 11.4 billion dollars in the next fiscal year, some
Iranian officials said earlier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report from London said that Iran's foreign
exchange deposit in international banks dropped to 7.46 billion
dollars by the end of last September, a reduction of 2.3 billion
dollars compared with the figure in June.
</P>
<P>
With the drop in foreign exchange revenue, the rate for dollar
against rial soared up to 5,130 rials Saturday in the black market
from 4,800 rials at the beginning of 1998, though the government
keeps the official rate at 1,750 rials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
