<HEADLINE> Survey: Shanghai Residents Say "No" to Discount Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that
nearly 70 percent of the residents in east China's Shanghai
municipality have a negative attitude toward discounted consumer
goods.
</P>
<P>
The sample survey by the municipal social economic survey team
revealed that only 30 percent of the 500 households surveyed are
willing to buy discount goods frequently while the other 70
percent first consider whether they really need the goods and the
quality of the goods.
</P>
<P>
Statistical experts said the results indicated a more mature
consumer attitude as residents pay more attention to their real
needs and commodity quality, rather than prices.
</P>
<P>
It also means that the residents have more money in their
pockets, said the experts.
</P>
<P>
As China has entered a period of a "buyer's market," businesses
are facing more fierce competition for consumers. To woo more
customers, discounting was in vogue in recent years in large
cities such as Shanghai and Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
