<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Decrease Orchard Are Because of Glut of Fruit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in central China's
Henan Province slashed the area devoted to growing fruit by 12.2
percent in 1997 compared to 1996, in response to the oversupply of
fruit on the market.
</P>
<P>
This is the first drop since 1991. The decrease is also a
reaction by increasingly market-savvy farmers toward fluctuations
in the market, said market experts.
</P>
<P>
Fruit from Henan are sold in many parts of country. Over the
past few years, orchards in the province had been expanding
rapidly, but the growth rate greatly exceeded the rise in fruit
consumption by rural and urban residents.
</P>
<P>
As a result, fruit growers' interests had been harmed because
of falling prices due to oversupply. Last year, the average fruit
growers' income in the province reportedly fell 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Henan, a leading agricultural production base in China,
produced 2.69 million tons of fruit last year, with a marked
increase in quality, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
Local officials were urged to give fruit farmers more guidance
in planting and inform growers of market situations for farm
products.
</P>
<P>
Fruit growers have started to increase investment in scientific
technology while adjusting their investment structure and
decreasing the area of orchards, said local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
