<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Phulbari Transit Route Remains Idle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A good dream has turned out a
fantasy. This is the sad fact facing the Phulbari alternative
transit route, which Nepal had clamored for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
Except the convoy of three trucks which moved along the route
to Bangladesh on the inauguration day on September 1, 1997, the
route has remained idle for the last six months.
</P>
<P>
The route runs 71 km from Kakarbhitta, Nepal's eastern gateway
to India, through Phulbari in northeastern India to the
Bangladeshi border town of Banglabandh.
</P>
<P>
Then it stretches another 580 km to the Mongla port in
southwestern Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Nepal had sought this transit route as an alternative to the
Calcutta port since 1978. It was reported that each year Nepal
loses millions of rupees in demurrage as chartered vessels
sometimes have to wait for several days to dock in the overcrowded
Calcutta and Haldia ports of India.
</P>
<P>
But India did not agree to the request until last June when
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral visited Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The land-locked Himalayan kingdom cheered to the news. It was
widely accepted that the new transit route would be sure to boost
Nepal's trade with Bangladesh and other countries as it offers a
short-cut access of Nepali products to Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
However, except the three trucks carrying pulses on the
inauguration day, no other vehicles ever rumbled on the route.
</P>
<P>
Calcutta remains the choice.
</P>
<P>
Chandi P. Shrestha, spokesman for Nepal's Ministry of Commerce,
explained that first of all the route was new, but impractical
operating modalities also contribute to the poor use of the route.
</P>
<P>
He said the route can be used only on Saturdays and Sundays,
official holidays for Nepal and Bangladesh, so traders have to
wait sometimes four to five days before they can enter Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Visa is required as well for entering Bangladesh, he told
Xinhua in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Ananda Raj Mulmi, president of the Federation of Nepalese
Chambers of Commerce and Industry, agreed.
</P>
<P>
Since visa facility is not available for them, local traders
had to come to Kathmandu to get the visas, he added.
</P>
<P>
There are other obstacles. The infrastructure in Bangladesh is
poor, roads are not in good condition, and bridges have to be
built, he said.
</P>
<P>
And the tariff for the Nepali traders is too high, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Then comes the payment system problem. Due to no access to U.S.
dollars, goods are purchased in local currencies.
</P>
<P>
Under the operating modalities, only pilfer-proof container
trucks can use the Phulbari transit route. The Nepali government
now only allows the government-owned companies to use the route,
but they do not have enough containers and the capacity of the
containers is very small, Mulmi said.
</P>
<P>
"Now the time has come for the government to permit the private
sector to provide service of containers," he said.
</P>
<P>
As Phulbari lies in the so-called "chicken neck" area which is
sensitive to India, the container trucks must be escorted by
Indian security troops and can move only in the daylight.
</P>
<P>
Mulmi said the Indian security troops can monitor, but not all
the time.
</P>
<P>
He said the Mongla port is the cheapest, yet the facilities
there are unavailable due to very little use.
</P>
<P>
But he is confident of the future. Bangladesh is short of
agricultural products, it imports them even from Latin America.
"Bangladesh thinks the Nepalese products are very good, so we see
a lot of chances," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Ambassador to Nepal Krishna V. Rajan said that in the
spirit of sub-regional cooperation among Bangladesh, Bhutan, India
and Nepal, the transit route was worked out through trilateral
efforts. But some practical problems need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
"We knew it could take some time before the route really
becomes attractive and viable," he said. "New modalities will need
to be worked out for the Nepali citizens to utilize the route."
</P>
<P>
"That's why the intention was to have a start on an
experimental basis and see and learn from the experience," he
added.
</P>
<P>
India has extended Nepal's use of the Phulbari route after the
six-month trial period expired. And commerce secretaries of the
two countries will meet in New Delhi later this month to review
the operating modalities.
</P>
<P>
"We'll see what's the best can be done in order to ensure that
commitment of India to provide a good and viable alternative
transit route to and through Bangladesh for Nepal is productive,"
the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the central issue is whether the business
community is seriously interested and motivated, and if so, then
other things like more investment in roads and bridges will follow
quickly.
</P>
<P>
And some practical measures will follow in India to address the
problems faced by the Nepali traders, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
