<HEADLINE> South China Province Cracking Down on Tax Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The economic powerhouse of
Guangdong Province in south China recovered more than 5.4 billion
yuan in tax fraud in the last three years, accounting for 6.2
percent of total local tax revenue, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial tax departments have dealt with 130,000 tax
violation cases during the period since the central government
adopted the revenue-sharing system in 1994, said Chen Jiaji,
deputy director of the local Tax Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The sum equals to the total annual tax revenue of four or five
medium-size cities in the province, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
By last year, Guangdong had set up 179 agencies with 1,767
officers to check on tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Tax departments have taken such measures as demanding overdue
taxes, fees, fines and confiscations to rectify tax-collecting
deficiencies and increase revenues, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Local tax bureaus have established a good reputation with the
public in settling major tax cases. The tax-evasion cases
involving the Zheng Wenyou Traditional Chinese Medicine Tumor
Hospital and a Japanese-funded golf company in Shenzhen had
attracted widespread attention and greatly promoted local tax
collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
