<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks Investment in Water Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has appealed to people to invest in the rehabilitation of the
rundown water supply facilities in the capital of Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The government, in cooperation with the World Bank, is seeking
investors to repair the rusty pipes to avert a water crisis in
the city, said Minister of Water Pius Ng'wandu Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The minister was addressing the press on this year's Water
Week which will start Monday, The Guardian paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The water ministry and the World Bank are planning to overhaul
the old water system in the region at a cost of 600 million US
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to invite people to buy shares," the newspaper
quoted Ng'wandu as saying.
</P>
<P>
Since the government cannot afford to spend so much money, it
is high time that people joined hands to invest in the water
sector, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"If common people can buy shares of the Tanzania Oxygen
Limited, why can't they do the same to water which is very
important to their daily life?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
There is also a need to increase water supply in Dar es Salaam
as only 35 percent of the water released from both Lower and
Upper Ruvu are able to reach people in the town, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
The last time when the regions's water system was repaired was
in 1989 during the course of harnessing the upper Ruvu river.
"This did not increase our water supply," he said, "it only
maintained the installed capacity of water."
</P>
<P>
"Most donors are prepared to rehabilitate the water system but
not to increase its capacity," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that all regions in the country will
evaluate the safe water supply systems and how to improve
services in this sector, as "underground water is a hidden
resource." 
</P>
</TEXT>
