<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Condemns DDT Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco industry and
environmental organizations have slammed the Ministry of Health
and Child Welfare for importing 10,000 tons of the lethal
chemical DDT for use in its malaria control programs.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for the Ministry Paulinus Sikhosana confirmed to the
Sunday Mail weekly that his ministry had procured 10,000 tons of
10 percent DDT to curb the high malaria incidence in most parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the concentration used for malaria control had in the
past been 75 percent DDT, the weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Banned in the western world, DDT was also a restricted
pesticide in Zimbabwe under the hazardous substances and articles
act of 1996. It was not banned locally, as it is registered for
public health use.
</P>
<P>
Sikhosana added that the World Health Organization still
recommended the use of DDT for malaria control for indoor
residual spraying, and countries like Botswana, Namibia and South
Africa still used the chemical for malaria control.
</P>
<P>
However, tobacco farmers complained that the hazardous
pesticide would affect their business as all tobacco with traces
of DDT or any other chemical was not acceptable in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco research board said it had identified two
small-scale farmers in the Nyanguza resettlement area with
unacceptable pesticide residue levels in the tobacco sent on the
floors. Upon investigation it was established that this had been
caused by the malaria-spraying exercise in 1997.
</P>
<P>
DDT in large quantities was known to cause cancer while the
1960s studies proved that it had led to the fall in the numbers
of birds, as it caused thinning of egg shells.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Environment 2000 condemned the procurement of
DDT, saying its use might have far-reaching implications on the
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
