<HEADLINE> Guilin Witnessed Increased Tax Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Guilin, a major tourism city in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, collected 8.98
million yuan (1.08 million US dollars) in value-added and
consumption taxes from foreign-funded enterprises in the first two
months of 1998, up 15 percent on the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Rising tax revenues have been attributed to achievements made
during 1997, a year in which tax revenues from the two items rose
14 percent to 97.6 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local officials also attributed growing revenue to the adoption
of strict tax collection measures. 
</P>
