<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- At least eight people were killed and 50 others
injured when an earthquake measuring 6.4 on the Richter scale
rocked central Iran before midnight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The quake struck the Golbaf region in Kerman province at about
11:12 p.m. (1942 GMT), the official Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) reported.(Iran-Earthquake)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid
Saturday accused the United States of meddling with other
countries' internal affairs when it brands Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein as a "war criminal."
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid was speaking to reporters a day after the
U.S. Senate voted to urge the creation of a United Nations
Tribunal to try Saddam Hussein as an international war criminal.
</P>
<P>
"Such matters which constitute interference in domestic affairs
are categorically rejected," he said before leaving here for Doha,
Qatar, to take part in the meetings of the foreign ministers of
the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) due to open on
Sunday. (Arab League-US-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Saturday called upon the United States, the main sponsor of
the Mideast peace process, to exert more efforts to restart the
long-stalled process.
</P>
<P>
"It is time for the U.S. to take action when it is not too
late," Moussa told reporters after Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak held talks with Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat on overcoming obstacles facing the peace process.
(Egypt-US-Peace Process)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad Saturday held talks
with his Lebanese counterpart Elias Hrawi on the latest
developments in the Middle East region, the Syrian News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said after a series of meetings that the two
countries insisted on the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad said that Syria will always stand by the Lebanese side
and support its efforts that are beneficial to the country's
national interests, stability and reconstruction. (Syria-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is going to
visit the Middle East next week to shore up support for his recent
agreement with Iraq on arms inspections, U.N. officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The visit will last nine days with stops in Jordan, Egypt,
Lebanon, Syria, Palestinian-controlled Gaza and Israel, but no
agenda has been fixed, said the officials who asked not to be
identified. (UN-Annan-Middle East Tour)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov Saturday called
for U.S. troops to replace the United Nations Preventive
Deployment Forces (UNPREDF) in his country.
</P>
<P>
The request, made in an interview aired by the country's
national television, was out of his concerns over the growing
ethnic tension in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
About half of the 700-strong UNPREDF are Americans. And its
U.N. Security Council mandate is to expire on August
31. (Macedonia-UN-Kosovo) 
</P>
