<HEADLINE> Pakistani Team Brings Light to Somali Blind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- It has been wonderful for the
blind in the Somali capital this week after a Pakistani team of
six doctors and nine nurses have undergone a massive operation in
restoring the eyesight to hundreds of Somalis in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Digfer General Hospital, the largest hospital here, has been
selected as the only site that could accommodate such major
operations in which 1,500-1,800 people were screened by the
doctors before the selections were made.
</P>
<P>
During their five-day operation which ended Saturday, the
Pakistani team from Al-Basar International Foundation funded by
Saudi Arabia had succeeded in restoring the eyesight to 709
people who mainly suffered from Cataract and Glaucoma which cause
blindness.
</P>
<P>
According to Dr Ali Basha Omar, the deputy chairman of a local
organization Al-Islah charity that invited and worked with the
Pakistani team, 70 out of the 709 people have been given lens
implant.
</P>
<P>
Omar also said that each of the 709 people was offered two
pairs of glasses, one of sun-glass and another of sight glass
free of charge. The patients were also given free treatment for
the first six weeks after the operation.
</P>
<P>
The people who benefited from the operation include 12
children who also lost their eye-sight.
</P>
<P>
Omar said the Pakistani team have conducted similar operations
in the town of Bossaso for three times, and six times in the
Northwestern town of Borama. The team will fly to the
northeastern region of Bossaso Monday for the same cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
