<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Build More Low Cost Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Building Society
(ZBS) has said it has allocated 400 million Zimbabwean Dollars
(25 million U.S. Dollars) for construction of low cost houses
this year.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by ZBS Managing Director Francis Nhema
Saturday while opening the institution's regional administration
center and main banking hall in Bulawayo, the country's second
largest city, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Financial shortages that have forced most established building
societies in the country to suspend housing projects.
</P>
<P>
Nhema said since its inception in 1992, the country's first
black-owned building society had invested more than 1.5 billion
Zimbabwean Dollars (90 million U.S. Dollars) in provision of
housing for Zimbabwe's tens of thousands low income earners.
</P>
<P>
"Although it is now difficult to meet the national vision of
housing for all by the year 2000, we are still fighting hard that
when we reach the year, at least the target will not be too far
off," said Nhema. 
</P>
