<HEADLINE> Suspected Fake Dollars Dealers Arrested in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police have arrested four
more west Africans suspected to be part of the fake U.S. Dollar
syndicate as some local businessmen have been swindled out of
113.7 million Kwacha (about 75,000 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times of Zambia reported Sunday that the tricksters who
allegedly claim to counterfeit Dollars once given money to buy
chemicals to process some material, last week swindled four
businessmen out of a total of the 113.7 million Kwacha in
separate incidents.
</P>
<P>
One businessman was cheated out of 45 million Kwacha after the
tricksters promised him a five percent commission of the three
million Dollars they were supposed to be counterfeit.
</P>
<P>
Three other businessmen were swindled out of 68.7 million
Kwacha. The trickster were supposed to counterfeit 2.5 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Acting Police Spokesman Lemmy Kajoba said out of the four
suspects, two were picked up in Chipata in eastern province and
two others in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
In the Chipata incident, the two were apprehended after they
tried to swindle some businessmen of Asian origin through the
same method. But the deal fell through after the businessmen
became suspicious and alerted the police.
</P>
<P>
A total of nine people have been picked up in connection with
the counterfeiting syndicate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
