face sixth-seeded Greg Rusedski of Britain on Sunday for the first
time Sunday in an all left-handed battle to vie for the Cup's
title.
</P>
<P>
The sixth-ranked Rusedski outlasted 20th-ranked Thomas Muster
7-6 (7-5), 6-1 in a 59-minute semifinal. Muster was playing
injured after sustaining a right hip injury during his
quarter-final match against Andrei Medvedev of the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Rios came back on the court after a lengthy two hour, four
minute rain delay at 6-6 in the first set and immediately took
charge of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
"I've played a lot of matches like that," Rios said. "You just
have to come back. You get used to it. What you got to do, just
get ready for the first point and win the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
For the second consecutive day, Rusedski created an on-court
earthquake by rocketing the fastest serve ever recorded. In the
11th game of the first set, Rusedski ended a love service game
with a 240 kph ace down the middle of the court to beat his
one-day-old world record of a 235 kph ace. 
</P>
