<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, Germany Strike Deal on Debt Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has reached a deal with
Germany allowing it to wipe out more than two thirds of its total
amount owed to the debtor nation.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Finance Minister Muravei Radev and his German
counterpart Jurgen Stark signed the agreement Friday, newspaper
reports said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Bulgaria will pay Germany 344 million
Deutsche marks, or 190 million U.S. dollars under current rate,
from 2001 to 2018, plus an annual interest of 3.4 percent starting
1999.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria owes Germany about 1.2 billion marks (670 million
dollars), and the two countries have been at odds for years on
issues concerning the debt amount and the way of repayment.
</P>
<P>
As required by the European Union (EU), Bulgaria should settle
its debts with individual EU nations before becoming eligible for
the second phase of financial assistance from the economic bloc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
