<HEADLINE> Macedonia Invites U.S. Troops to Replace UNPREDF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov
Saturday called for U.S. troops to replace the United Nations
Preventive Deployment Forces (UNPREDF) in his country.
</P>
<P>
The request, made in an interview aired by the country's
national television, was out of his concerns over the growing
ethnic tension in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
About half of the 700-strong UNPREDF are Americans. And its
U.N. Security Council mandate is to expire on August 31.
</P>
<P>
If Washington doesn't want to send troops, Gligorov was quoted
as saying by reports from the Macedonian capital of Skoplje, the
UNPREDF's mandate should be extended by at least six months.
</P>
<P>
He called for a political solution in Kosovo, noting that
neither crackdown nor intervention can resolve the problem there.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian president also expressed deep concerns over new
Western sanctions against Belgrade, saying such punitive move will
inevitably inflict harms to neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
He criticized recent demonstrations by ethnic Albanians in
Macedonia in support of their counterparts in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
