<HEADLINE> 60 Drowned as Two Launches Capsize in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 60 people were feared drowned
and over 100 others were injured when two boats capsized in a
violent storm in the Kalpetua river in southwest Bangladesh on
Friday afternoon, press reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two launches, each carrying about 100 passengers against
their capacity of 50, went down in the river in Satkhira, some 170
km southwest of here, when a tornado hit the region, survivors
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two launches capsized within a distance of one km during
the storm that swept over Satkhira, Chuadanga and Kushita
districts.
</P>
<P>
Police said they had recovered 25 bodies from the river and the
launches were salvaged Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"More than two-thirds of the passengers swam ashore after the
accidents, while the others were drowned or missing," a police
official said.
</P>
<P>
A survivor said the driver of one of the launches ignored
passengers' calls for a halt when the storm came.
</P>
<P>
A three-member committee, led by the additional district
magistrate, has been formed to probe the accident, the reports
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
