<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospitality Industry to Change Strategy to Maintain Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis sweeping
Southeast Asian countries has cast a shadow over Beijing's hotel,
forcing them to pay more attention to attracting domestic
customers, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Customers from Chinese mainland have already accounted for 43
percent of the Holiday Inn Downtown Beijing hotels business,
general manager Dominic Wong said, but that proportion would
increase to 55 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of tourist and business travelers will
definitely be hit by the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, which
gradually shows its impact, this year.
</P>
<P>
Since tourism is an "expensive exercise," it will be one of the
first things abandoned by people if they run into financial
problems, he said, adding that business people from Southeast Asia
will also cut their trips to China if their business is hit by the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He predicts that Beijing average hotel occupancy rate and
prices would suffer double-digit declines though the crisis'
impact on local hotel business would not so damaging as in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
To offset the impact, he said, the hotel will adopt a flexible
pricing strategy and improve its services to consolidate its
customer resources, in addition to adjusting its traditional
business strategy, from just focusing on individual business
travelers to groups.
</P>
<P>
Another hotel, the Beijing International Club Hotel (BIC),
ITT's Sheraton's only investment in china, is confident that its
prospects are good despite the general gloom in the hotel market
provoked by the Southeast Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese economic outlook is still looking strong with many
new projects starting every day, and business is still looking
very good," said Katie Benson, the BIC hotel's general manager.
</P>
<P>
Benson admitted the financial crisis in Southeast Asia will
lead to a decline in tourist coming into China, but she did not
think it would have much impact on her hotel's business.
</P>
<P>
The hotel mainly targets government delegations, top managerial
staff and individual travelers who need luxuriously appointed
accommodation and top-quality personal services.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the stable economic growth of China, ITT Sheraton
regards it as one of the most important countries in its business
development strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
