<HEADLINE> Drought Reduces Longan Yield in Northern Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 rai (8,000
hectares) of longan orchards in Thailand's northern province of
Lampang will produce the worst yield in a decade due to heavy
drought, Sunday's Bangkok Post quoted a local agricultural
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
This will bring heavy losses to the local growers, who have
spent much on more expensive chemical fertilizers and will have to
spend more to dig wells for their trees to survive the drought,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Some growers predicted that their income this year will shrink
by as much as 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lampang Governor Chalermphol Pratheepavanit said on
Saturday that he had ordered the province's 13 district chiefs to
distribute sand bags to every village so that its people could
block the main waterways and store water for farming and home use.
</P>
<P>
The governor predicted that the drought, a result of the El
Nino weather phenomenon, will become critical next month,
affecting the province's main water source, the Wang river.
</P>
</TEXT>
