<HEADLINE> Bulls Turn Cautious on BSE Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Equities failed to maintain its
initial gains on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market during the
week as bulls later turned cautious with the Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) falling short of a clear majority in the Lower House
of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Another factor is BJP's Tamil Nadu allies' hesitancy to commit
support in writing to the proposed coalition.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index rose to 3,807.1 at close on Monday but
later dipped to 3,691.20 during Wednesday's trade, before ending
the week at 3,716.50 as against last weekend's close of 3,708.58,
netting a modest gain of 7.92 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index was fractionally down at 1,602.95 at the
weekend from the previous weekend's close of 1,603.54. The BSE-200
and US dollar index were quoted slightly lower at 354.34 and
149.31 compared with the last weekend close of 355.12 and 149.76
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade was low at 48,770.2 million rupees
(1,266.76 million US dollars) as compared with last week's
turnover of 59,261.8 million rupees (1,539.27 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Foreign institutional investors and domestic institutions
preferred to keep away from the market due to the stalemate on the
political front. 
</P>
