<HEADLINE> Educational Circles Urged to Contribute to Reemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), in session here since early March, called
on China's educational circles to offer a helping hand for the
reemployment of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the country has 1,020
institutions of higher learning with more than 400,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
"Encouraging them to play an active role in vocational training
is an effective way to help with reemployment programs," said
Prof. Liu Zhongshu, an NPC deputy and president of Jilin
University.
</P>
<P>
Yu Jianhua, a professor at Liaoning University of Engineering
and Technology professor, suggested that colleges and universities
should open free or low-cost training courses for laid-off workers
in evenings or on weekends.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zixuan, an economics professor from Beijing University,
urged the Beijing Municipal Government to give guidance to the
city's 67 institutions of higher learning and 483 research
institutes so as to contribute to the success of reemployment
programs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Peng Kunchi, president of Shanxi University, said,
"Both the government and enterprises require us to train laid-off
workers, and we should do whatever they expect us to do, so as to
repay what we have received from society." 
</P>
