<HEADLINE> Hickman Swims Golden Double in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHEFFIELD, England, March 14 (Xinhua) -- World short-course
champion James Hickman savored a golden double on the first day of
a World Cup swimming meet here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hickman produced an excellent performance to become the third
fastest man ever in the 200 meters butterfly, winning by more than
half a length in one minute 53.19 seconds and beating compatriot
Roger Ashcroft by nearly nine seconds.
</P>
<P>
Later, Hickman completed a fine day by winning the 100 meters
individual medley in 55.26 seconds, beating Croatias Milos
Milosevic by 0.95 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen-year-old Yoshiko Saito, the youngest finalist, stunned
her elders in the women's 200 meters backstroke to give Japan its
second win of the day after Tatsuya Kinugasa took the men's 400
meters individual medley.
</P>
<P>
Kinugasa outraced Canadian Olympic and world championship
bronze medallist Curtis Myden by 0.05 seconds to win in 4:13.86.
</P>
<P>
Australia collected two victories through Lori Munz in the
women's 200 individual medley and Ryan Mitchell in the men's 200
breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell enjoyed a margin of one second against Britain's Adam
Whitehead, who edged Australian world record holder Phil Rogers
into third place by 0.01 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Patrik Isaksson, 100 breaststroke gold medallist at
last April's world short-course championships in Gothenburg,
dominated the men's 50 breaststroke in which he beat second-placed
Rogers by 0.56 seconds in 27.84.
</P>
<P>
Fellow world short-course champion Jacob Carstensen of Denmark
produced a similarly commanding win in the 400 freestyle ahead of
Britain's Ian Wilson.
</P>
<P>
Sandra Voelker, winner in the 50 meters backstroke in 28.55
seconds, was beaten in the women's 50 meters freestyle by fellow
German Katrin Meissner. Meissner clocked 25.17 and Voelker 25.28.
</P>
<P>
Sydney, Hong Kong, Beijing and Rio de Janeiro staged the first
four meetings this year while Sheffield opens the final European
phase of the World Cup, which moves on to Malmo, Sweden,
Gelsenkirchen, Germany, Imperia, Italy and Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
