<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Latin American Trade Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Sino-Latin American trade is
expected to keep growing, according to today's "Business Weekly."
</P>
<P>
Last year witnessed a massive growth in Chinese exports to the
region of 47.7 per cent, bringing the total to 4.6 billion
U.S. Dollars, while the imports from Latin American also went up,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper called it a significant achievement for China, which
has been trying since 1990 to diversify its export markets, which
are currently concentrated in Asia, North America and Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The growth in Sino-Latin trade will be sustained by the steady
economic growth of both Latin America and China, said an official
from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the economies of China and the Latin
American countries are highly complementary and further trade and
economic cooperation potential are yet to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
A 20-day fact-finding mission of the China Chamber of Commerce
of Machinery and Electronic Product Importers and Exporters to
Brazil, Argentina and Chile drew the conclusion that Latin America
has a particularly large demand for machinery and electronic
imports.
</P>
<P>
Chinese exports of machinery and electronic products to the
region only make up a small proportion of such Chinese
exports. The ratio stood at two percent in 1996 and about 2.7
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Long distances, high transportation costs, lack of after-sales
services and little understanding of local needs are among the
major reasons for the limited volume of trade, the paper says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
