<HEADLINE> Russians Upstage Norwegians in Oslo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSLO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian cross-country skiers Alexei
Prokurorov and Larissa Lazutina won the final individual World Cup
events of the season in Oslo on Saturday, eclipsing Norwegian
stars on their home turfs.
</P>
<P>
Prokurorov, winning his first World Cup of the season, won the
50 km classic in two hours 32 minutes 25.3 seconds, beating four
Norwegians including ski ace Bjoern Daehlie to third.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie, who won three golds at the Nagano Olympics to make him
the most successful Winter Olympian of all time with eight golds,
said he was happy with the result.
</P>
<P>
"It was a good race for me. I haven't done very well after
Nagano...My form has been off and I feel that the spring is
coming," he said.
</P>
<P>
Norway's Thomas Alsgaard, who had secured the overall World Cup
title ahead of Daehlie before Saturday's race, ended in 20th
place, more than nine minutes adrift of Prokurorov.
</P>
<P>
Russian Olympic star Lazutina showed crushing form by winning
the women's 30 km race by more than two minutes in a time of one
hour 41 minutes 41.2 seconds.
</P>
<P>
In the Nordic combined, Mario Stecher of Italy was best in
Saturday's ski jumping ahead of Norway's Bjarte Engen Vik, setting
up a duel for Sunday's 15 km cross country that will decide the
overall World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
Stecher jumped longest on Saturday, with a leap of 127.0
metres, giving himself a 26 second start over the Norwegian for
Sunday. 
</P>
