<HEADLINE> Opposition Against Cuba Embargo Grows in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A former U.S. diplomat said here
Saturday the opposition to the U.S. economic sanction against Cuba
is growingly strong in his country.
</P>
<P>
Wayne Smith, former head of the U.S. Office of Interests in
Cuba, told the Cuban press that also stronger is the call for
lifting the embargo of food and medicine to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Smith was in a group of U.S. businessmen and former officials
staying here since Wednesday for a week-long visit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. government officials have already acknowledged the failure
of the so-called Helms-Burton Act, which was signed into law by
President Bill Clinton on March 12, 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
Initially designed to further tighten up the grip on the Cuban
people, the U.S. legislation is totally counter-productive for the
very interests of the United States, the former diplomat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
