<HEADLINE> Pakistan FM Leaves for OIC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan left here Saturday night for Qatar to attend the
foreign ministers' meeting of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) which will begin on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers are expected to discuss a wide range of
issues concerning the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the conference includes Kashmir and Pakistan
expects a strong endorsement of its position on the issue during
the conference, according to sources from the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad visited Qatar last
week with a special message from Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif for
the Amir of Qatar.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman from the Foreign Ministry, the message
contained Pakistan's viewpoint on regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
The issues of Palestine and Kashmir, and the situation in
Afghanistan have been on the agenda of the OIC foreign ministers'
meeting for sometime.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming meeting will explore possibilities for greater
cooperation among OIC member countries in the economic and
scientific fields.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also review the progress in the implementation
of decisions taken at the eighth OIC summit held in Tehran in
December last year.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting in Qatar, Ayub Khan will travel to Geneva
where he will attend the 52nd U.N. session on human rights
scheduled for March 17-21.  
</P>
