<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Output Up in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Peru increased rice output and
reduced the import of the crop in the last three years, the
Agriculture Ministry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The area cultivated with rice was up 17.9 percent, from 203,196
hectares in 1995 to 239,625 hectares in 1997, bringing the output
to the historic high of 1,459,500 metric tons.
</P>
<P>
As results, rice imports last year were down 43 percent from
the previous year, to a total of 234,124 tons; and further down 55
percent in the first two months of this year, to 26,900 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Ministry attributed the drop of imports to the
measures taken by the government to protect the home agriculture,
including a 12 percent tariff and an additional 5 percent surtax.
</P>
<P>
In addition, at the beginning of this year, the government
decided to suspend the imports of rice from 51 countries where the
cultivation were affected by pest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
