<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Postma Beefs up Lead at All-Round Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEERENVEEN, Netherlands, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Defending
champion Ids Postma not only tightened his grip on the world title
but also moved within easy reach of breaking the world record at
the World All-Round Speedskating Championships on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
World titlist Gunda Niemann-Stirnemann fared even better as the
German skater broke a world record while more than closing her
grip on the world title.
</P>
<P>
Niemann-Stirnemann clocked 4 minutes 5.08 seconds in the day's
3,000-meter race for the new world mark, shattering the previous
one of 4:07.13 held by countrywoman Claudia Pechstein.
</P>
<P>
Postma beat compatriot Rintje Ritsma by one hundredth of a
second in the nail-biting men's 1,500-meter race, finishing 1
minute 48.85 seconds ahead of Ritsma's 1:48.86.
</P>
<P>
He now leads the men's pack with 112.072 points, followed by
Ritsma and KC Boutiette of the United States on 112.924 and
114.331 points respectively.
</P>
<P>
Postma's accumulated total may well break the listed world mark
of 155.966 points posted by Japan's Keiji Shirahata who created it
last January during the Japanese national championships at Nagano.
</P>
<P>
Niemann-Stirnemann also improved her opportunity for yet
another world mark en route to defending her world title by
finishing first in both of Saturday's races of the 1,500 and 3,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
She now garnered a leading total of 120.979 points, followed by
two other Germans, Pechstein and Anni Friesinger on 121.099 and
122.668 points.
</P>
<P>
Niemann-Stirnemann clocked 1:58.69 in the shorter race.
</P>
<P>
The German skater also holds the current world record of
165.708 points for the all-round total.
</P>
<P>
Only the top 16 skaters from the previous three races will be
eligible for Sunday's grand finale of the men's 10,000 meters and
women's 5,000 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
