<HEADLINE> China Wins Three Gold Medals At All England Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, March 14 (Xinhua) - China's Sun Jun, the world
No.2, overwhelmed Ong Ewe Hock to win the men's singles title at
the 88th All England Open Championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After his victory over compatriot Luo Yigang in the semi-final
on Friday, the 22-year-old Chinese toppled the Malaysian 15-1,
15-7, who surprisely ousted Denmark's Pete Gade, the world No 1 on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a post-match press briefing, Ong Ewe Hock said: "Sun is very
strong and powerful. These days I have been very tired and I
couldn't even follow his speed."
</P>
<P>
In the women singles final, defending champion Ye Zhaoying
retained her title by defeating her Chinese compatriot Zhang Ning,
who outplayed the world No 1 Gong Zhichao in the semi-final Friday.
</P>
<P>
The women's doubles title went to Chinese Ge Fei and Gu Jun who
overpowered Jang Hye Ock and Ra Kyung Min from South Korea 15-7,
15-7.
</P>
<P>
On the women's doubles final, Simon Reed, the commentator from
Sky TV said: "The triple-title holders are invincible. Every time
people watch their performence, the pair will give you something
new." 
</P>
