<HEADLINE> EU Drops World Cup Threat to Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the European
Union (EU) who were holding a two-day imformal meeting in
Edinburgh Saturday, dismissed the idea of kicking Yugoslavia out
of this year's soccer World Cup finals as a sanction against
Yugoslavia over the Kosova crisis.
</P>
<P>
Swedish foreign minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen, who is attending
the meeting, suggested on Friday expelling Yugoslavia's national
soccer team if Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic failed to
open talks with Kosovans on the autonomy for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But his counterparts from Britain, France and Germany all
raised objections to the move.
</P>
<P>
British foreign secretary Robin Cook told a news conference
that a World Cup ban was not within the competence of the EU while
German foreign minister Klaus Kinkel said political sports
boycotts had not produced the desired results in the past.
</P>
<P>
French foreign minister Hubert Vedrine pointed out that the
idea had been dropped by the six-nation Contact Group at its
meeting in London last Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the meeting urged Milosevic to open negotiations or face
further sanctions. 
</P>
