<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Not to Sponsor Resolution Critical of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
has decided to give up its bid to sponsor a U.N. resolution
critical of China's human rights record in spite of mounting
pressure from Congress.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Eric Rubin told AP Saturday that the U.S.
decision came after China agreed to sign the Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights, a move hailed here as a significant step
forward.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken note of a number of positive developments in the
human rights situation in China," Rubin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
China's Deputy Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen told a
press conference Thursday that his country was prepared to ink the
pact, which guarantees freedom of thought, conscience, religion
and expression.
</P>
<P>
Both the White House and the State Department responded
positively to the Chinese announcement, saying it would have
"significant" impact on moves to be taken by the U.S. at the
upcoming Geneva meeting of the U.N. Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
The comment was seen as a hint of no more bid to seek a censure
on China as the U.N. Human Rights Commission prepares to meet next
week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate passed a resolution Thursday, urging the
Clinton administration to come forward with an anti-China
resolution at the Geneva meeting. But the administration cited
sights of improvement in China's human rights situation to justify
its intention to head off confrontation with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, President Bill Clinton expressed satisfaction at
China's "swift and firm" response to U.S. concerns about a
possible sale of chemical to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced that he decided to move up his trip to China
to June to maintain the momentum of improvement in relationship
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The president cited China's response as an "example" for
cooperation on nonproliferation, standing firmly on his early
certification to Congress that China abides by the principles of
nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
The certification, if not rejected by Congress, will result in
hundreds of millions of U.S. dollars of nuclear equipment sales to
China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's bid can be overturned only if both houses of Congress
vote to disapprove it. Outcome seems unlikely because only a few
days remain before certification becomes final under a
congressionally-mandated deadline, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decided not to censure China on human rights this year
after it realized that it might be more isolated among its allies
if it stands where it was as the European Union decided earlier to
back off.
</P>
<P>
The annual resolution sought by the U.S. and its Western allies
since 1990 has never been adopted by the 53-member U.N.
commission. Even the senators who pushed hard for such a
resolution have admitted that the prospect became dimmer this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post aired Saturday the belief that the
administration is seeking a new policy toward China on the human
rights issue by pressing Beijing to sign international human
rights covenants.
</P>
<P>
"We have determined there are other, more promising ways to
pursue improving the human rights situation," Rubin of the White
House said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980315.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Executive Proposes to Streamline Traffic Bans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, has proposed that EU member
states wishing to limit the time when lorries may travel on roads
should observe a harmonized system.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal by the EU executive, the system should
require its member states to notify the commission of any plans
they may have in this realm, according to European Report, a
newsletter published in Brussels Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The commission's proposal seeks to guarantee unimpeded movement
of goods from one member state to another, while recognizing the
justification for some national restrictions in the light of
environmental, social and safety considerations.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive also wants the harmonized system to focus on
the period and traffic times as well as on the types of vehicles
and operations concerned. The system should also include night
bans on noisy lorries as well as a series of specific exemptions,
according to the commission.
</P>
<P>
European Report said the proposal is in part a reaction to the
present confusion caused by a lack of coordination between the
bans on lorries at weekends and during public holidays.
</P>
<P>
This type of ban is being applied in seven EU member states --
Germany, Austria, Spain, France, Italy, Luxembourg and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
However, the systems differ considerably from one country to
another. The holiday periods, the time when the ban starts and
ends, exemptions and the category of lorries involved vary
considerably, with the result that hauliers are finding it
difficult to plan their journeys properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
