<HEADLINE> Annan Begins Middle East Trip Next Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is going to visit the Middle East next week to shore up
support for his recent agreement with Iraq on arms inspections,
U.N. officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The visit will last nine days with stops in Jordan, Egypt,
Lebanon, Syria, Palestinian-controlled Gaza and Israel, but no
agenda has been fixed, said the officials who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief will spend several days at the U.N. headquarters
in Geneva before he begins his trip to the region next Wednesday,
the officials told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who successfully averted a threatened U.S. and British
military strike against Iraq, will mainly brief leaders of
governments in the region of his deal with the Iraqi government on
February 23 as well as the recent progress in the U.N. weapons
inspections in Baghdad, Annan's aides told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But the U.N. chief has denied that he is going to take a role
in the Middle East peace process, launched in Madrid in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Annan's aides said that his visit is part of his duty of
visiting every region of the world as the U.N. chief at the
invitation of governments.
</P>
<P>
Annan was to go to the Middle East last month but finally
postponed the trip because of the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the Middle East conflict is concerned, the parties
have a mediator," Annan said during his visit to Washington
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the United States: it is President Clinton, Mrs Albright
(Secretary of State) and Dennis Ross (the State Department's chief
negotiator for the Middle East)," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
He said that he believes "a multiplicity of mediators often
confuses the issue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
