<HEADLINE> Sudanese President on Relations With Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
al-Bashir instructed Saturday the relevant ministries to make
necessary arrangements for reconsidering the status of the
Egyptian interests on the Sudanese territories.
</P>
<P>
The instructions are in line with the policies of the Sudanese
government which seek to remove all the long-standing obstacles
that had hindered the development of the bilateral ties, the
Sudanese News Agency quoted Al-Bashir as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government closed the Egyptian schools and the
Khartoum branch of Cairo University, and confiscated some Egypt's
property on its territory when the bilateral ties were
strained over the past years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had accused Sudan of sheltering Egyptian militants bent
on installing a strict Islamic state in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Cairo also accused Khartoum of supporting an attempt to kill
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, in
1995. Sudan denied the charge and blasted Egypt for letting in
members of Sudanese opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
However, the bilateral relations began improving over the past
few months. After a hiatus of more than three years, Egypt resumed
the river Nile navigation from the Egyptian High Dam to the
Sudanese port of Halfa in mid-February, a move hailed by both
sides as a sign of improving relations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir phoned the Egyptian president on Friday and hailed
the noticeable improvement of the bilateral relations, indicating
Sudan's desire to push its ties with Egypt forward.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa will
hold talks with his Sudanese counterpart Mustafa Ismail in Cairo
on March 23 on the sidelines of meetings of the Arab League
Council.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili met with Sudanese
Minister of Trade Osman el-Hadi, who is now visiting here.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed ways of increasing the volume of trade
exchange between the two countries, said Goweili after the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
