<HEADLINE> EU Monetary Officials Locked in Drachma Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Senior European Union (EU)
monetary officials were locked in talks Saturday over how to allow
the Greek currency drachma to make its debut in the planned
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Greece Friday asked other EU member states to let the drachma
enter the Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM), part of its bid to gain
market credibility and improve its chances of joining Europe's
much-vaunted single currency.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Sweden and Denmark have announced not to join the
first wave of EMU countries while Greece, struggling with high
inflation, is having difficulty in meeting the EU's rigorous
qualification criteria. The EMU is scheduled to be launched on
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, Greece wants to show its enthusiasm about EMU by
signing up first to the European Monetary System's ERM.
</P>
<P>
The EU's secretive monetary committee, composed by senior
finance ministry and central bank officials from the 15 EU member
states, was still discussing at what rate the drachma could come
into the ERM after meeting for over four hours in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
A Greek Finance Ministry official was quoted as saying that
central bankers wanted to devalue the drachma by 14 percent but
politicians were pressing for less.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear whether Greece's request for ERM entry, and the
likely drachma devaluation, could trigger a broader realignment of
other EU moneys already within the ERM basket.
</P>
<P>
Months of speculation that the ERM could be realigned ahead of
EMU's January 1999 launch had focused on a possible revaluation of
the Irish punt which has traded well above its bilateral central
rate against the German mark.
</P>
<P>
However, Greek and Irish officials earlier refused to make any
comment as they arrived for the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
