<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges U.S. Devotion to Mideast Peace-making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Saturday called upon the United States, the main sponsor of
the Mideast peace process, to exert more efforts to restart the
long-stalled process.
</P>
<P>
"It is time for the U.S. to take action when it is not too
late," Moussa told reporters after Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak held talks with Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat on overcoming obstacles facing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egypt is also waiting to see the results of the
contacts as British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook is taking to the
Mideast a European initiative on reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"What matters is how to deal with the Israeli rejection of
implementing the Oslo agreements and other relevant resolutions,"
said Moussa, adding that there will be a number of alternatives if
the European initiatives fail.
</P>
<P>
"But we are waiting for what the current contacts will result
in, specially as regards the stance to be adopted by the U.S. in
its capacity as the main peace sponspor that is responsible for
making a drive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite repeated mediation by the U.S. and other parties, the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked for nearly a
year over Israeli construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cairo on Saturday afternoon, a day before
Cook launches his six-leg tour of the region to float the European
initiative that calls on Israel to withdraw from the West Bank and
halt Jewish settlement activities, while urging the Palestinians
to guarantee Israeli security demands.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, a frequent visitor of Cairo for consulations with
Egyptian leaders on Mideast peace, came here amid rampant Arab
unrest in the Palestinian self-rule areas over the killing of
three Palestinian workers by Israeli soldiers on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Despite those events, the Palestinian side will remain
committed to the signed agreements, Arafat told reporters upon
his arrival, urging the world community to put pressure on the
Israeli government to comply with these U.S.-brokered
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will leave for Doha to attend the Islamic foreign
ministers meetings scheduled to open on Sunday. 
</P>
