<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Wants Tougher Checks on Goods Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, wants all lorries and
utility vehicles to meet uniform roadworthiness and maintenance
standards.
</P>
<P>
A draft directive, which the EU executive has recently
unveiled, was an attempt to bridge existing gaps in the inspection
mechanism already applied throughout Europe, according to European
Report, a newsletter published in Brussels Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This system requires an annual technical inspection of heavy
goods vehicles used for road transport, said the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
The draft directive provides for the 15 EU member states to
carry out additional random inspections of these vehicles on the
roads, in ports, in parking areas or in hauliers' own premises.
</P>
<P>
If an inspection reveals that a vehicle fails to meet standards
for safety and environmental protection and consequently
constitutes a major risk for its occupants or other road-network
users, it may immediately be ordered off the road. 
</P>
</TEXT>
