<HEADLINE> Algerian FM Holds Talks with U.S. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Algerian Foreign Minister Ahmed
Attaf held talks here Saturday with Matin Indyk, visiting
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for the Middle East and North
African Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The talks dealt with bilateral relations and the parliamentary
exchanges between the two countries, according to the Algerian
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed regional and international issues,
particularly the recent agreement between the United Nations and
Iraq over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The meeting provided an opportunity for Attaf to brief the
U.S. official on the situation in Algeria in light of the recent
political and economic reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
Algerian Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia met with Indyk Saturday
morning who conveyed to him a message from U.S. President Bill
Clinton to Algerian President Liamine Zeroual.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Clinton expressed hope that cooperation between
Algeria and the United States will develop on the bilateral and
the multilateral levels.
</P>
<P>
Indyk arrived here Friday evening for a one-day visit to
Algeria as part of a tour that has taken him to Tunisia, and will
take him to Morocco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
